// MedMasters : Gynae & Obs Paper 2: Infections
// 150 MCQs | Perinatal & Postoperative Infections, Communicable Diseases, COVID-19, Dengue, Malaria
(function(){
  if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
  window.MM['gynae_p2_infections'] = [
    {q:'The most common cause of puerperal sepsis after delivery is:',
  o:['Staphylococcus aureus','Clostridium perfringens','Escherichia coli','Streptococcus pyogenes'],a:3,
  e:`Key organisms involved in puerperal sepsis are Lancefield group A beta-haemolytic streptococcus (Streptococcus pyogenes) and Escherichia coli: over 50% of puerperal sepsis deaths are due to group A streptococcus.<br><br>Until 1937, puerperal sepsis was the major cause of maternal mortality; the discovery of sulphonamides in 1935 led to a dramatic fall.<br><br>Staphylococcus aureus (A), Clostridium perfringens (B) and E. coli (C) are all associated with puerperal infection but are less common than group A streptococcus as the primary cause.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Puerperal fever is defined as temperature ≥38°C occurring after:',
  o:['First 12 hours postpartum','First 24 hours postpartum','First 48 hours postpartum','First 72 hours postpartum'],a:1,
  e:`Significant puerperal pyrexia is defined as a temperature of 38°C or higher on any 2 of the first 10 days postpartum, exclusive of the first 24 hours.<br><br>A mildly elevated temperature is not uncommon in the first 24 hours, and in about 80% of women who develop a temperature in this window after vaginal delivery, no obvious evidence of infection can be identified.<br><br>12 hours (A), 48 hours (C) and 72 hours (D) do not match the standard clinical definition of puerperal fever.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common source of postpartum infection is:',
  o:['Respiratory tract','Urinary tract','Genital tract','Surgical incision'],a:2,
  e:`Puerperal infection is usually polymicrobial and involves contaminants from the bowel that colonize the perineum and lower genital tract: following delivery, natural barriers to infection are temporarily removed and organisms ascend from the lower genital tract into the uterine cavity.<br><br>Placental separation exposes a large raw area equivalent to an open wound, providing an excellent culture medium for ascending genital tract organisms.<br><br>Respiratory tract (A), urinary tract (B) and surgical incision (D) are recognised sites of puerperal pyrexia but are not the most common source of postpartum infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The most important risk factor for puerperal infection is:',
  o:['Early rupture of membranes','Short labor','Maternal obesity','Caesarean section'],a:3,
  e:`The risk of sepsis is higher following caesarean section, particularly when performed after the onset of labour: this is the most important single risk factor for puerperal infection, which is why routine prophylactic antibiotics are given before the skin incision.<br><br>A single intraoperative dose of co-amoxiclav or cephalosporin with metronidazole is standard practice to reduce post-caesarean infection.<br><br>Early rupture of membranes (A) and maternal obesity (C) are recognised risk factors; short labour (B) is not a risk factor.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Endometritis after delivery most commonly presents with:',
  o:['Severe hypertension','Fever with uterine tenderness','Haematuria','Severe jaundice'],a:1,
  e:`Infection spreading into the myometrium and parametrium gives rise to an endometritis: symptoms include fever, rigors, abdominal discomfort, offensive lochia and a boggy, tender, larger uterus on examination.<br><br>Women with endometritis classically have uterine tenderness with fever : distinguishing it from retained placental tissue, which is the other common cause of secondary PPH.<br><br>Severe hypertension (A) suggests pre-eclampsia; haematuria (C) indicates urinary tract pathology; severe jaundice (D) is not a feature of endometritis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common organism responsible for post-caesarean wound infection is:',
  o:['Pseudomonas aeruginosa','Klebsiella pneumoniae','Enterococcus species','Staphylococcus aureus'],a:3,
  e:`Staphylococcus aureus is the most common organism responsible for post-caesarean wound infection, causing localised redness, warmth, swelling and pus discharge at the incision site.<br><br>The problem with resistant bacteria such as methicillin-resistant S. aureus (MRSA) has led some units to routinely screen all women admitted electively to prevent their spread.<br><br>Pseudomonas (A), Klebsiella (B) and Enterococcus (C) are all associated with polymicrobial puerperal infections but are not the primary cause of wound infection after caesarean section.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which microorganism is classically associated with gas gangrene in obstetric infections?',
  o:['Escherichia coli','Streptococcus viridans','Clostridium perfringens','Staphylococcus epidermidis'],a:2,
  e:`Necrotizing fasciitis is a rare but frequently fatal infection of skin, fascia and muscle that can originate in perineal tears, episiotomies and caesarean section wounds: a variety of bacteria can be involved, but anaerobes predominate and Clostridium perfringens is usually identified.<br><br>In addition to general signs of infection, there is extensive necrosis, crepitus and inflammation requiring wide debridement under general anaesthesia.<br><br>E. coli (A) is a common aerobic pathogen in puerperal infection; Streptococcus viridans (B) and S. epidermidis (D) are not associated with gas gangrene.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The most effective preventive measure for postoperative infection after caesarean section is:',
  o:['Routine blood transfusion','Prophylactic antibiotics','Early ambulation','Intravenous fluids'],a:1,
  e:`The risk of sepsis following caesarean section can be prevented by routine prophylactic antibiotics: a single intraoperative dose of co-amoxiclav or cephalosporin with metronidazole is given before the skin incision.<br><br>Increased awareness of general hygiene, good surgical approach and aseptic techniques have all contributed to the decline in severe puerperal sepsis.<br><br>Routine blood transfusion (A) has no role in infection prevention; early ambulation (C) and IV fluids (D) support recovery but are not the primary preventive measure.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Septic pelvic thrombophlebitis usually presents with:',
  o:['Persistent fever despite antibiotics','Severe anaemia','Hypoglycaemia','Severe jaundice'],a:0,
  e:`Infection from the uterus can be carried by uterine vessels into the inferior vena cava via iliac vessels, giving rise to septic thrombophlebitis: the hallmark presentation is persistent spiking fever that fails to respond to broad-spectrum antibiotics.<br><br>The diagnosis is clinical; treatment involves therapeutic anticoagulation in addition to antibiotics, with fever typically resolving within 48–72 hours of heparin.<br><br>Severe anaemia (B), hypoglycaemia (C) and severe jaundice (D) are not characteristic features of septic pelvic thrombophlebitis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common bacteria causing postpartum urinary tract infection is:',
  o:['Proteus mirabilis','Staphylococcus saprophyticus','Enterococcus faecalis','Escherichia coli'],a:3,
  e:`Escherichia coli is the most common causative organism in postpartum urinary tract infection, as it is in UTIs generally: it colonises the perineum from the bowel and ascends the urinary tract, particularly in the context of catheterisation during labour.<br><br>Common sites associated with puerperal pyrexia include chest, throat, breasts, urinary tract, pelvic organs, caesarean or perineal wounds and legs.<br><br>Proteus (A) and Staphylococcus saprophyticus (B) can cause UTIs but are less common postpartum; Enterococcus faecalis (C) is more frequently associated with pelvic infections.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Necrotizing fasciitis following caesarean section is most commonly caused by:',
  o:['Streptococcus pyogenes','Staphylococcus aureus','Clostridium perfringens','Pseudomonas aeruginosa'],a:0,
  e:`Necrotizing fasciitis can originate in perineal tears, episiotomies and caesarean section wounds: a variety of bacteria can be involved, but group A streptococcus (Streptococcus pyogenes) and anaerobes predominate, with Clostridium perfringens also commonly identified.<br><br>Wide debridement of necrotic tissue under general anaesthesia is absolutely essential, alongside management of septic shock, to avoid mortality.<br><br>Staphylococcus aureus (B) causes wound infections; Clostridium perfringens (C) is associated with gas gangrene specifically; Pseudomonas (D) is a gram-negative aerobe less commonly the primary cause.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common site of infection after caesarean delivery is:',
  o:['Lungs','Surgical wound','Kidney','Endometrium'],a:3,
  e:`Following caesarean section, placental separation exposes a large raw area within the uterus and the endometrium becomes the most common site of infection: endometritis following caesarean delivery is significantly more common than after vaginal delivery.<br><br>The caesarean wound should also be considered; in women delivering by caesarean section, a wound infection should be evaluated when pyrexia is present.<br><br>Lungs (A) and kidneys (C) are recognised sites of puerperal pyrexia; surgical wound (B) is the second most common site but endometritis predominates.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which condition predisposes most strongly to puerperal sepsis?',
  o:['Maternal diabetes','Premature rupture of membranes','Anaemia in pregnancy','Short second stage'],a:1,
  e:`Prolonged rupture of membranes is a major risk factor for puerperal infection, as it allows ascending contamination of the amniotic cavity with vaginal flora before and during delivery, substantially increasing the risk of chorioamnionitis and subsequent endometritis.<br><br>Common risk factors for puerperal infection include chorioamnionitis, prolonged rupture of membranes, cervical cerclage, prolonged labour, multiple vaginal examinations, instrumental delivery, caesarean section and retained products of conception.<br><br>Maternal diabetes (A) and anaemia (C) are background risk factors; short second stage (D) is not a recognised risk factor.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'A foul-smelling lochia in the postpartum period suggests:',
  o:['Normal postpartum discharge','Retained placental tissue only','Physiological involution','Septic infection of uterus'],a:3,
  e:`Offensive lochia is a cardinal symptom of puerperal pelvic infection: it indicates bacterial colonisation of the retained blood and debris within the uterine cavity, signalling underlying endometritis or parametritis.<br><br>Other symptoms of puerperal pelvic infection include malaise, headache, fever, rigors, abdominal discomfort, vomiting and secondary PPH.<br><br>Normal lochia progresses from red to serosa to alba over about a month and should not be offensive; retained placental tissue (B) causes secondary PPH and may coexist with, but does not alone explain, foul smell.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The most important route of infection in puerperal sepsis is:',
  o:['Haematogenous spread','Lymphatic spread','Ascending infection from vagina','Direct spread from bowel'],a:2,
  e:`An ascending infection from the lower genital tract or primary infection of the placental site is the most common method of spread in puerperal sepsis: organisms ascend from the lower genital tract into the uterine cavity when natural barriers are temporarily removed after delivery.<br><br>The infection may then spread via the Fallopian tubes to the ovaries, giving rise to salpingo-oophoritis and pelvic peritonitis, or directly into the myometrium causing endometritis.<br><br>Haematogenous (A) and lymphatic (B) spread are secondary routes that can carry infection to distant sites once established; direct bowel spread (D) is not the primary mechanism.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which organism is commonly associated with polymicrobial postpartum infections?',
  o:['Streptococcus pneumoniae','Mycobacterium tuberculosis','Neisseria gonorrhoeae','Bacteroides species'],a:3,
  e:`Puerperal infection is usually polymicrobial and involves contaminants from the bowel that colonise the perineum and lower genital tract: anaerobes : particularly Bacteroides species including B. fragilis, B. bivius and B. disiens : are consistently identified in polymicrobial puerperal infections.<br><br>Bacteroides fragilis is also the most common anaerobic organism involved in pelvic infections generally.<br><br>Streptococcus pneumoniae (A) causes respiratory infections; M. tuberculosis (B) causes TB; Neisseria gonorrhoeae (C) causes gonorrhoea but is not the primary organism in polymicrobial puerperal sepsis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common breast infection during lactation is:',
  o:['Breast abscess','Mastitis','Fibroadenoma','Galactocele'],a:1,
  e:`Mastitis is the most common breast infection during lactation: it occurs when a blocked duct obstructs the flow of milk and distends the alveoli, and the affected segment appears red and oedematous with flu-like symptoms, tachycardia and pyrexia.<br><br>The pyrexia with infective mastitis typically develops in the third to fourth postpartum week and persists for longer than that of breast engorgement.<br><br>Breast abscess (A) develops in about 10% of women with mastitis and is a complication, not the primary infection; fibroadenoma (C) and galactocele (D) are not infective conditions.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Lactational mastitis is most commonly caused by:',
  o:['Streptococcus pneumoniae','Pseudomonas aeruginosa','Escherichia coli','Staphylococcus aureus'],a:3,
  e:`The most common infecting organism in lactational mastitis is S. aureus, which is found in 40% of women with mastitis: other organisms include coagulase-negative staphylococci and Streptococcus viridans.<br><br>If mastitis worsens, a sample of milk should be taken for microbiological culture and flucloxacillin commenced while awaiting sensitivity results.<br><br>Streptococcus pneumoniae (A), Pseudomonas aeruginosa (B) and E. coli (C) are not the primary organisms in lactational mastitis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common symptom of postpartum endometritis is:',
  o:['High fever and uterine tenderness','Severe hypertension','Haematuria','Polyuria'],a:0,
  e:`Infection spreading into the myometrium gives rise to endometritis: symptoms include fever, rigors and abdominal discomfort, while signs include pyrexia, tachycardia and a boggy, tender, larger uterus.<br><br>Offensive lochia and secondary PPH may also be present; both endometritis and retained placental tissue cause secondary PPH, and the two conditions often coexist.<br><br>Severe hypertension (B) suggests pre-eclampsia; haematuria (C) indicates urinary tract pathology; polyuria (D) is not a feature of endometritis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The first-line management of puerperal sepsis is:',
  o:['Oral co-amoxiclav only','Intravenous broad-spectrum antibiotics','Surgical drainage alone','Observation only'],a:1,
  e:`With severe infections, immediate high-dose broad-spectrum antibiotics and resuscitation with intravenous fluids are provided on a high-dependency unit: mild to moderate infections can be treated with broad-spectrum antibiotics such as co-amoxiclav or cephalosporin plus metronidazole, with the first doses given intravenously.<br><br>Close liaison with microbiologists and internal medicine specialists is vital in severe cases.<br><br>Oral antibiotics alone (A) are insufficient for established puerperal sepsis; surgical drainage (C) is required for abscesses, not as first-line; observation only (D) is never appropriate for sepsis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which complication can result from untreated puerperal infection?',
  o:['Septic shock','Gestational diabetes','Placenta praevia','Polyhydramnios'],a:0,
  e:`With severe infections, there is a release of inflammatory and vasoactive mediators in response to endotoxins produced during bacteriolysis: the resultant local vasodilatation causes circulatory embarrassment and poor tissue perfusion, known as septicaemic, septic or endotoxic shock.<br><br>Delay in appropriate management could be fatal; features of septic shock include hypotension, tachycardia, oliguria and altered consciousness.<br><br>Gestational diabetes (B), placenta praevia (C) and polyhydramnios (D) are not complications of untreated puerperal infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which sign suggests severe postpartum infection progressing to sepsis?',
  o:['Mild headache','Bradycardia','Increased appetite','Tachycardia and hypotension'],a:3,
  e:`The features of septicaemic or endotoxic shock include tachycardia and hypotension resulting from vasodilatation and circulatory embarrassment caused by endotoxins released during bacteriolysis.<br><br>With severe infections, resuscitation with intravenous fluids and immediate high-dose broad-spectrum antibiotics on a high-dependency unit are essential; delay could be fatal.<br><br>Mild headache (A) and increased appetite (C) are not signs of sepsis; bradycardia (B) is the opposite of what occurs in septic shock.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Pelvic abscess after delivery most commonly develops in the:',
  o:['Broad ligament','Inguinal region','Rectouterine pouch','Retroperitoneal space'],a:2,
  e:`An ascending infection from the lower genital tract may spread via the Fallopian tubes to the ovaries, giving rise to salpingo-oophoritis and pelvic peritonitis, which could progress to the development of pelvic abscesses: the rectouterine pouch (pouch of Douglas) is the most dependent part of the pelvis and therefore the most common site for pelvic abscess formation.<br><br>Bogginess in the pelvis on examination is a sign of abscess formation in the rectouterine pouch.<br><br>Broad ligament (A), inguinal region (B) and retroperitoneal space (D) are not the primary sites for puerperal pelvic abscess.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common pathogen causing neonatal infection from maternal genital tract infection is:',
  o:['Streptococcus agalactiae (Group B)','Staphylococcus aureus','Escherichia coli','Listeria monocytogenes'],a:0,
  e:`Group B streptococcus (Streptococcus agalactiae) is recognised as the most frequent cause of severe early-onset infection in newborn infants: it can cause sepsis in the neonate and transmission occurs from the time the membranes rupture until delivery.<br><br>Approximately 21% of women in the UK carry GBS as a vaginal commensal; the mortality from early-onset GBS disease is 6% in term infants and 18% in preterm infants.<br><br>Staphylococcus aureus (B) and E. coli (C) cause neonatal infections but are not the most common; Listeria (D) causes neonatal infection through transplacental spread.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Which condition significantly increases the risk of postoperative pelvic infection after gynaecological surgery?',
  o:['Early ambulation','Adequate hydration','Prophylactic iron therapy','Poor surgical sterility'],a:3,
  e:`Increased awareness of the principles of general hygiene, a good surgical approach and the use of aseptic techniques have all contributed to the decline in severe puerperal sepsis: poor surgical sterility remains a significant avoidable risk factor for postoperative pelvic infection.<br><br>Every clinician should use alcohol hand rubs regularly in clinical areas, at least between every patient contact.<br><br>Early ambulation (A) and hydration (B) support recovery; prophylactic iron (C) addresses anaemia but does not directly reduce infection risk.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which complication may occur from severe pelvic infection after surgery?',
  o:['Pelvic abscess formation','Polycythaemia','Hyperthyroidism','Increased fertility'],a:0,
  e:`An ascending infection from the lower genital tract may spread via the Fallopian tubes to the ovaries, giving rise to salpingo-oophoritis, pelvic peritonitis and ultimately pelvic abscess formation: this could progress to generalised peritonitis.<br><br>Infection may also spread to distant sites via lymphatics and blood vessels, giving rise to septic thrombophlebitis, pulmonary infections or generalised septicaemia.<br><br>Polycythaemia (B), hyperthyroidism (C) and increased fertility (D) are not complications of pelvic infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which organism is most commonly responsible for toxic shock syndrome after gynaecological surgery?',
  o:['Escherichia coli','Bacteroides fragilis','Staphylococcus aureus','Streptococcus pneumoniae'],a:2,
  e:`Toxic shock syndrome is caused primarily by Staphylococcus aureus through the production of toxic shock syndrome toxin-1 (TSST-1): it presents with fever, rash, hypotension and multiorgan involvement, and is associated with tampon use and post-surgical wound infection.<br><br>The problem with resistant bacteria such as MRSA has led some units to screen all women admitted electively to prevent their spread.<br><br>E. coli (A) and Bacteroides fragilis (B) are associated with gram-negative sepsis and anaerobic infections respectively; Streptococcus pneumoniae (D) causes pneumonia, not toxic shock syndrome.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'A breast abscess is most commonly a complication of:',
  o:['Mastitis','Galactocele','Fibroadenoma','Breast carcinoma'],a:0,
  e:`About 10% of women with mastitis develop a breast abscess, diagnosed using ultrasound: treatment is by a radial surgical incision and drainage under general anaesthesia.<br><br>Cracked nipples : caused by poor positioning of the baby on the breast : increase the risk of breast abscess by providing an entry point for S. aureus.<br><br>Galactocele (B) is a sterile milk-filled cyst and is not infective; fibroadenoma (C) and breast carcinoma (D) are not infective conditions and do not lead to abscess formation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which infection may develop at the episiotomy site postpartum?',
  o:['Surgical wound infection','Pelvic thrombosis','Liver abscess','Episiotomy wound infection'],a:3,
  e:`Vaginal delivery is almost invariably associated with lacerations of the genital tract including episiotomy, which can become a focus for infection similar to iatrogenic wounds such as caesarean section: episiotomy wound infection is a recognised postpartum complication presenting with localised redness, swelling and discharge.<br><br>Perineal infections from necrotizing fasciitis can extend rapidly to involve the buttocks, thighs and lower abdominal wall.<br><br>Pelvic thrombosis (B) and liver abscess (C) are not episiotomy-site complications; surgical wound infection (A) is a broader term that encompasses episiotomy infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which preventive measure reduces postpartum infection risk the most?',
  o:['Strict aseptic technique during delivery','Routine analgesics','Prolonged hospital stay','Late ambulation'],a:0,
  e:`Increased awareness of the principles of general hygiene, a good surgical approach and the use of aseptic techniques have all contributed to the decline in severe puerperal sepsis: every clinician should use alcohol hand rubs regularly, at least between every patient contact.<br><br>Although it is over 150 years since Ignaz Semmelweis identified the importance of handwashing for preventing spread of infection, poor attention to hand hygiene remains a significant problem.<br><br>Routine analgesics (B), prolonged hospital stay (C) and late ambulation (D) do not reduce infection risk.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Septicaemia in postpartum infection is characterised by:',
  o:['Mild fever only','Isolated urinary infection','Local wound infection only','Bacteria in bloodstream with systemic illness'],a:3,
  e:`With severe infections, there is a release of inflammatory and vasoactive mediators in response to endotoxins produced during bacteriolysis: infection from the uterus carried by uterine vessels into the inferior vena cava via iliac vessels gives rise to septic thrombophlebitis, pulmonary infections or generalised septicaemia.<br><br>The resultant circulatory embarrassment and poor tissue perfusion is known as septicaemic, septic or endotoxic shock.<br><br>Mild fever only (A) and local wound infection (C) describe less severe stages; isolated urinary infection (B) is a separate entity without systemic bacteraemia.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which postoperative infection typically presents with localised redness, warmth, and pus discharge?',
  o:['Urinary infection','Wound infection','Pneumonia','Septicaemia'],a:1,
  e:`Wound infection : whether at a caesarean or episiotomy site : classically presents with localised redness, warmth, induration and pus discharge at the incision: in women delivering by caesarean section, a wound infection should always be considered when pyrexia is present.<br><br>Common sites associated with puerperal pyrexia include caesarean or perineal wounds, and these require direct inspection.<br><br>Urinary infection (A) presents with dysuria and frequency; pneumonia (C) with respiratory symptoms; septicaemia (D) with systemic haemodynamic compromise without necessarily localised signs.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common anaerobic organism involved in pelvic infections is:',
  o:['Lactobacillus','Streptococcus pneumoniae','Bacteroides fragilis','Haemophilus influenzae'],a:2,
  e:`Anaerobes : particularly Bacteroides species including B. fragilis, B. bivius and B. disiens : are consistently identified in puerperal pelvic infections: puerperal infection is usually polymicrobial and involves contaminants from the bowel that colonise the perineum and lower genital tract.<br><br>Bacteroides fragilis is notably resistant to many antibiotics, which is why metronidazole is included in the standard prophylactic and treatment regimens.<br><br>Lactobacillus (A) is a normal vaginal commensal and not pathogenic; Streptococcus pneumoniae (B) and Haemophilus influenzae (D) are respiratory pathogens not typically involved in pelvic infections.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which condition increases infection risk during labour due to repeated vaginal examinations?',
  o:['Prolonged labour','Early induction','Normal labour','Short labour'],a:0,
  e:`Common risk factors for puerperal infection include prolonged labour and multiple vaginal examinations: repeated vaginal examinations during prolonged labour introduce organisms from the lower genital tract into the uterine cavity when natural barriers are compromised.<br><br>Other intrapartum risk factors include instrumental delivery, caesarean section, manual removal of the placenta and retained products of conception.<br><br>Early induction (B) and normal labour (C) do not inherently increase infection risk; short labour (D) is associated with fewer examinations and lower infection risk.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Postpartum infection spreading through lymphatics may result in:',
  o:['Osteoporosis','Hyperthyroidism','Pelvic cellulitis','Diabetes mellitus'],a:2,
  e:`Infection may spread directly into the myometrium and parametrium, giving rise to an endometritis or parametritis : also referred to as pelvic cellulitis : when it travels through lymphatic channels: pelvic peritonitis and abscesses may also occur by this route.<br><br>Infection may also spread to distant sites via lymphatics and blood vessels, carrying organisms into the inferior vena cava and giving rise to septic thrombophlebitis or generalised septicaemia.<br><br>Osteoporosis (A), hyperthyroidism (B) and diabetes mellitus (D) have no association with puerperal infection spread.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which infection is characterised by inflammation of the breast tissue during lactation?',
  o:['Mastitis','Fibroadenoma','Breast cyst','Breast carcinoma'],a:0,
  e:`Mastitis is inflammation of the breast commonly related to breastfeeding problems: it occurs when a blocked duct obstructs the flow of milk and distends the alveoli, with the milk extravasating into the perilobular tissue and initiating an inflammatory process.<br><br>The affected segment appears painful, red and oedematous, with flu-like symptoms and pyrexia; the most common infecting organism is S. aureus, found in 40% of cases.<br><br>Fibroadenoma (B) and breast cyst (C) are non-infective benign conditions; breast carcinoma (D) is a malignancy unrelated to lactational inflammation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which clinical feature is most suggestive of necrotizing infection after surgery?',
  o:['Mild wound discharge','Localised bruising','Severe pain with tissue necrosis','Mild erythema only'],a:2,
  e:`Necrotizing fasciitis is a rare but frequently fatal infection of skin, fascia and muscle: in addition to general signs of infection, there is extensive necrosis, crepitus and inflammation : severe pain disproportionate to appearance with visible tissue necrosis is the hallmark clinical feature.<br><br>Wide debridement of necrotic tissue under general anaesthesia is absolutely essential to avoid mortality, alongside management of septic shock.<br><br>Mild wound discharge (A) and mild erythema (D) suggest simple wound infection; localised bruising (B) is not specific to necrotizing infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which systemic complication can occur from severe puerperal infection?',
  o:['Septic shock','Polycythaemia','Gestational diabetes','Placenta praevia'],a:0,
  e:`With severe infections, there is a release of inflammatory and vasoactive mediators in response to endotoxins produced during bacteriolysis: the resultant vasodilatation causes circulatory embarrassment and poor tissue perfusion : the phenomenon known as septicaemic, septic or endotoxic shock.<br><br>Delay in appropriate management could be fatal; immediate high-dose broad-spectrum antibiotics and resuscitation with intravenous fluids are essential.<br><br>Polycythaemia (B), gestational diabetes (C) and placenta praevia (D) are not systemic complications of puerperal infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which infection control practice is most important to prevent hospital-acquired obstetric infections?',
  o:['Frequent blood testing','Prolonged bed rest','Routine vitamin supplements','Proper hand hygiene'],a:3,
  e:`Although it is over 150 years since Ignaz Semmelweis identified the importance of handwashing for preventing spread of infection between postnatal women, poor attention to hand-washing remains a significant problem: every clinician should use alcohol hand rubs regularly in clinical areas, at least between every patient contact.<br><br>The arrival of alcohol hand-based hand rubs has facilitated the process and remains the most important single infection control practice.<br><br>Frequent blood testing (A), prolonged bed rest (B) and routine vitamins (C) have no proven role in preventing hospital-acquired obstetric infections.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'Which route is the most common pathway for bacteria causing postpartum uterine infection?',
  o:['Haematogenous spread','Ascending infection from vagina','Transplacental spread','Direct bowel perforation'],a:1,
  e:`An ascending infection from the lower genital tract or primary infection of the placental site is the most common pathway: following delivery, natural barriers to infection are temporarily removed and organisms with pathogenic potential ascend from the lower genital tract into the uterine cavity.<br><br>Placental separation exposes a large raw area equivalent to an open wound, and retained products of conception and blood clots within the uterus provide an excellent culture medium.<br><br>Haematogenous spread (A) and transplacental spread (C) are secondary or antenatal routes; direct bowel perforation (D) is a surgical complication, not a common postpartum pathway.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common route of mother-to-child transmission of HIV is:',
  o:['During labor and delivery','Through breast milk','During first trimester','Via placental transfer in second trimester'],a:0,
  e:`Mother-to-child transmission of HIV mainly occurs in the late third trimester, during labour, delivery or breastfeeding: the principal risks of vertical transmission are related to maternal plasma viral load, obstetric factors and infant feeding.<br><br>Interventions to reduce the risk of vertical transmission : including antiretroviral therapy, elective caesarean section with high viral load and avoidance of breastfeeding : can reduce transmission from 25–30% to less than 2%.<br><br>Breastfeeding (B) is a significant secondary route; first trimester (C) and second trimester placental transfer (D) contribute minimally compared to intrapartum transmission.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The most important screening test for HIV during pregnancy is:',
  o:['Western blot','CD4 count','ELISA test','Viral load measurement'],a:2,
  e:`In the UK, all pregnant women should be offered screening for HIV early in pregnancy because appropriate antenatal interventions can reduce maternal-to-child transmission from 25–30% to less than 2%: the ELISA (enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay) test detecting HIV antibodies is the standard screening tool.<br><br>Routine antenatal screening has increased detection rates and new treatments have dramatically increased life expectancy.<br><br>Western blot (A) is a confirmatory test used after a positive ELISA; CD4 count (B) monitors immune status; viral load (D) guides treatment decisions but is not the primary screening test.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The most effective intervention to reduce vertical transmission of HIV is:',
  o:['Antiretroviral therapy','Elective caesarean section alone','Formula feeding only','Vitamin supplementation'],a:0,
  e:`Antiretroviral therapy given antenatally and intrapartum to the mother and to the neonate for the first 4–6 weeks of life is the cornerstone of preventing vertical transmission: all women who are HIV positive should be advised to take antiretroviral therapy during pregnancy and at delivery.<br><br>Combined with avoidance of breastfeeding and elective caesarean section when viral load is high, transmission can be reduced from 25–30% to less than 2%.<br><br>Elective caesarean section alone (B) and formula feeding alone (C) are components of the strategy but are not independently the most effective intervention; vitamin supplementation (D) has no role in preventing vertical HIV transmission.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Hepatitis B virus is primarily transmitted through:',
  o:['Faecal-oral route','Blood and body fluids','Respiratory droplets','Mosquito bite'],a:1,
  e:`Hepatitis B is transmitted through blood and body fluids: acute hepatitis B infection occurs in 1–2 per 1,000 pregnancies and 1.5% of pregnant women are chronic carriers, with transmission occurring through sexual contact, blood-to-blood contact and vertically from mother to infant.<br><br>Without preventive measures, 90% of babies born to mothers with hepatitis B will contract the infection.<br><br>Faecal-oral route (A) transmits hepatitis A and E; respiratory droplets (C) transmit influenza and COVID-19; mosquito bite (D) transmits dengue and malaria.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 2: Antenatal Care)</em>`},

    {q:'Which marker indicates active infectivity in hepatitis B infection?',
  o:['HBsAb','HBcAb','Anti-HBs','HBeAg'],a:3,
  e:`HBeAg (hepatitis B e antigen) is a marker of active viral replication and high infectivity: its presence indicates that the virus is actively replicating in the liver and that the mother is highly infectious, significantly increasing the risk of vertical transmission to the neonate.<br><br>Hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) indicates the presence of hepatitis B in the blood; HBeAg positivity additionally signals high replicative activity.<br><br>HBsAb and Anti-HBs (A, C) indicate immunity : either from vaccination or past infection; HBcAb (B) indicates past or current infection but not specifically high infectivity.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 2: Antenatal Care)</em>`},

    {q:'The most effective method to prevent neonatal hepatitis B infection is:',
  o:['HBV vaccine plus HBIG at birth','Maternal treatment only','Breastfeeding avoidance only','Elective caesarean section'],a:0,
  e:`The infant should receive hepatitis B vaccine and one dose of hepatitis B immune globulin (HBIG) within the first 12 hours of life: this confers over 95% protection against chronic hepatitis B infection, with additional doses of hepatitis B vaccine given at 1 and 6 months of age.<br><br>Without preventive measures, 90% of babies born to mothers with hepatitis B will contract the infection.<br><br>Maternal treatment alone (B) reduces viral load but is insufficient without neonatal prophylaxis; breastfeeding avoidance (C) and elective caesarean section (D) are not recommended as standalone preventive strategies for hepatitis B.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 2: Antenatal Care)</em>`},

    {q:'Hepatitis C virus is mainly transmitted through:',
  o:['Respiratory droplets','Faecal-oral route','Blood exposure','Mosquito bite'],a:2,
  e:`Hepatitis C is transmitted primarily through blood-to-blood contact: the prevalence of hepatitis C in pregnant women is estimated at 1–2%, and it is associated with adverse pregnancy outcomes including preterm rupture of membranes and gestational diabetes, as well as low birthweight in neonates.<br><br>Testing for HCV involves detection of anti-HCV antibodies in serum with confirmatory testing by PCR if positive.<br><br>Respiratory droplets (A) transmit respiratory viruses; faecal-oral route (B) transmits hepatitis A and E; mosquito bite (D) transmits dengue and malaria.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The risk of vertical transmission of hepatitis C increases significantly when the mother also has:',
  o:['HIV infection','Gestational diabetes','Thyroid disease','Anaemia'],a:0,
  e:`A caesarean delivery is recommended for women with hepatitis C who are also HIV positive, as the risk of vertical transmission of hepatitis C is higher in the context of HIV coinfection: there is no strong evidence regarding mode of delivery in women with hepatitis C alone.<br><br>Consensus groups do not recommend elective caesarean section for all hepatitis C women; the recommendation applies specifically to those who are also HIV positive.<br><br>Gestational diabetes (B), thyroid disease (C) and anaemia (D) do not specifically increase hepatitis C vertical transmission risk.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Hepatitis A virus is mainly transmitted by:',
  o:['Blood transfusion','Sexual contact','Respiratory aerosol','Faecal-oral route'],a:3,
  e:`Hepatitis A is transmitted via the faecal-oral route through contaminated food and water: the incidence of hepatitis A in pregnancy is around 1 in 1,000 and fetal transmission is extremely rare, making it a less dangerous hepatitis virus in the obstetric context.<br><br>The clinical features of hepatitis A are no different to the non-pregnant patient and it is generally self-limiting.<br><br>Blood transfusion (A) and sexual contact (B) transmit hepatitis B and C; respiratory aerosol (C) does not transmit hepatitis A.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'The hepatitis virus associated with high maternal mortality during pregnancy is:',
  o:['Hepatitis A','Hepatitis E','Hepatitis C','Hepatitis B'],a:1,
  e:`Hepatitis E is more likely to lead to fulminant hepatic failure in pregnancy: in underdeveloped countries, 20% of women infected in the third trimester die of fulminant hepatitis, making it the hepatitis virus with the highest maternal mortality in pregnancy.<br><br>It is more common in primigravidae and in the third trimester, with significant associations with preterm delivery, fetal growth restriction and stillbirth.<br><br>Hepatitis A (A) is generally self-limiting; hepatitis C (C) causes chronic disease but rarely acute maternal death; hepatitis B (D) is serious but carries lower acute maternal mortality than hepatitis E.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'Parvovirus B19 infection during pregnancy can cause:',
  o:['Neural tube defects','Shoulder dystocia','Macrosomia','Fetal hydrops'],a:3,
  e:`Slapped cheek syndrome (erythema infectiosum or fifth disease) is caused by parvovirus B19: the main effect on the fetus is severe anaemia leading to fetal hydrops, as the virus preferentially infects erythroid precursors and causes aplastic anaemia in the fetus.<br><br>Middle cerebral artery Doppler can be performed to confirm fetal anaemia; if confirmed, intrauterine blood transfusion can be considered to prolong the pregnancy until recovery.<br><br>Neural tube defects (A) are related to folate deficiency; shoulder dystocia (B) and macrosomia (C) are obstetric complications unrelated to parvovirus infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The mechanism of fetal hydrops in parvovirus B19 infection is:',
  o:['Severe fetal anaemia','Placental insufficiency','Cardiac malformation','Renal failure'],a:0,
  e:`The main effect of parvovirus B19 infection is severe anaemia in the fetus, as the virus infects erythroid precursor cells and causes aplastic anaemia: this severe fetal anaemia leads to high-output cardiac failure, fluid accumulation and hydrops fetalis.<br><br>Doppler ultrasound of the middle cerebral artery is used to detect fetal anaemia; faster flow is indicative of anaemia and guides decisions regarding intrauterine transfusion.<br><br>Placental insufficiency (B) causes FGR, not hydrops; cardiac malformation (C) and renal failure (D) are not the mechanism of parvovirus-associated hydrops.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common sexually transmitted infection worldwide is caused by:',
  o:['Treponema pallidum','Neisseria gonorrhoeae','Herpes simplex virus','Human papillomavirus'],a:3,
  e:`Human papillomavirus (HPV) infection is the most common sexually transmitted infection worldwide, with the primary route of transmission being sexual contact: it is most strongly associated with cervical cancer, particularly through persistent infection with high-risk types 16 and 18.<br><br>The HPV vaccine protecting against types 6, 11, 16 and 18 has been introduced in national immunisation programmes to reduce cervical cancer incidence.<br><br>Treponema pallidum (A) causes syphilis; Neisseria gonorrhoeae (B) causes gonorrhoea; herpes simplex virus (C) causes genital herpes : all common STIs but less prevalent than HPV globally.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'Human papillomavirus infection is most strongly associated with:',
  o:['Ovarian cancer','Cervical cancer','Endometrial cancer','Vulval varicosities'],a:1,
  e:`HPV infection : particularly persistent infection with high-risk types 16 and 18 : is the most strongly associated cause of cervical cancer: the vaccine protecting against these types has been introduced in national programmes to reduce cervical cancer incidence.<br><br>HPV infection may also present as genital warts (condyloma acuminata) caused by low-risk types 6 and 11.<br><br>Ovarian cancer (A) and endometrial cancer (C) have different aetiologies; vulval varicosities (D) are not related to HPV infection.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'The HPV types most commonly associated with cervical cancer are:',
  o:['6 and 11','31 and 33','18 and 45','16 and 18'],a:3,
  e:`HPV types 16 and 18 are the high-risk oncogenic types most strongly associated with cervical cancer: together they account for approximately 70% of all cervical cancers worldwide, making them the primary targets of the HPV vaccine.<br><br>Types 6 and 11 are low-risk types associated with genital warts (condyloma acuminata) but not cervical cancer.<br><br>Types 6 and 11 (A) cause warts; types 31 and 33 (B) and 18 and 45 (C) are associated with cervical cancer but are less common than types 16 and 18.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'Genital herpes is caused by:',
  o:['Human papillomavirus','Herpes simplex virus','Cytomegalovirus','Varicella zoster virus'],a:1,
  e:`Genital herpes is caused by herpes simplex virus (HSV), typically HSV-2 for genital infections and HSV-1 for oral-labial infections, though both types can affect either site: it characteristically presents with painful vesicular ulcers and urinary retention.<br><br>HSV infection causes genital herpes and typically presents with painful ulcers; this distinguishes it from syphilis (painless chancre) and HPV (painless warts).<br><br>Human papillomavirus (A) causes warts and cervical disease; cytomegalovirus (C) causes congenital infection; varicella zoster (D) causes chickenpox and shingles.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'Neonatal herpes infection is most commonly acquired:',
  o:['Transplacentally in first trimester','During breastfeeding','During vaginal delivery','Through respiratory droplets'],a:2,
  e:`Neonatal herpes is most commonly acquired during vaginal delivery when the neonate passes through the birth canal in the presence of active maternal genital herpes lesions: this is the primary route of neonatal HSV infection and the reason caesarean section is recommended in active infection.<br><br>The risk is highest with primary maternal HSV infection at the time of delivery, which has not allowed time for protective maternal antibodies to develop and transfer to the fetus.<br><br>Transplacental first-trimester transmission (A) occurs rarely; breastfeeding (B) is not a significant route unless breast lesions are present; respiratory droplets (D) do not transmit HSV.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The recommended mode of delivery in active genital herpes infection is:',
  o:['Caesarean section','Vaginal delivery with antiviral prophylaxis','Instrumental delivery','Vacuum extraction'],a:0,
  e:`Caesarean section is recommended in active genital herpes infection to prevent neonatal herpes acquired during passage through the birth canal: the risk of neonatal herpes is highest with primary maternal infection at delivery, when maternal antibodies have not yet developed.<br><br>Antiviral agents such as aciclovir, used in primary HSV infection, have dramatically improved outcomes when complications occur.<br><br>Vaginal delivery with antivirals (B) does not adequately reduce neonatal transmission risk in active infection; instrumental delivery (C) and vacuum extraction (D) are not recommended as they increase the risk of neonatal inoculation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The most sensitive test for diagnosing HIV infection is:',
  o:['Western blot','PCR test','ELISA antibody test','Viral culture'],a:1,
  e:`PCR (polymerase chain reaction) directly detects viral nucleic acid and is the most sensitive test for HIV diagnosis, particularly in neonates: maternal antibodies crossing the placenta are detectable in most neonates of mothers who are HIV positive, meaning neonates test positive for HIV antibodies by ELISA : direct viral amplification by PCR is therefore used for the diagnosis of infant infections.<br><br>PCR tests are typically carried out at birth, then at 3 weeks, 6 weeks and 6 months.<br><br>Western blot (A) is a confirmatory test; ELISA (C) is the primary screening test but less sensitive than PCR; viral culture (D) is slow and not used clinically.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'TORCH infections include:',
  o:['Toxoplasmosis, others, rubella, cytomegalovirus, herpes','Tuberculosis, oral herpes, rubella, chlamydia, hepatitis','Tetanus, osteomyelitis, rubella, cytomegalovirus, herpes','Toxoplasmosis, otitis media, rubella, candida, hepatitis'],a:0,
  e:`TORCH is an acronym for Toxoplasmosis, Others (syphilis, varicella, parvovirus B19, HIV), Rubella, Cytomegalovirus and Herpes simplex: these are the major perinatal infections capable of crossing the placenta and causing congenital anomalies.<br><br>Screening in pregnancy includes testing for rubella immunity, syphilis, hepatitis B, HIV and cytomegalovirus where indicated.<br><br>Options B, C and D all contain incorrect organisms and do not represent the established TORCH classification.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Congenital toxoplasmosis most commonly results from infection acquired:',
  o:['During adolescence','Before pregnancy','During pregnancy','After delivery'],a:2,
  e:`Congenital toxoplasmosis results from primary maternal Toxoplasma gondii infection acquired during pregnancy, typically through ingestion of undercooked meat or contact with cat faeces: the risk of fetal infection increases with gestational age, but the severity of fetal damage is greatest when infection occurs early in pregnancy.<br><br>Serological testing showing positive IgM for Toxoplasma gondii indicates recent primary infection.<br><br>Infection acquired during adolescence (A) or before pregnancy (B) results in immunity, not congenital disease; infection after delivery (D) poses no risk to the already-born infant.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The classic triad of congenital toxoplasmosis includes:',
  o:['Chorioretinitis, hydrocephalus, intracranial calcifications','Deafness, microcephaly, cataracts','Hydrops, anaemia, jaundice','Rash, fever, hepatosplenomegaly'],a:0,
  e:`The classic triad of congenital toxoplasmosis is chorioretinitis, hydrocephalus and intracranial calcifications: these result from the parasite's tropism for neural tissue, causing periventricular calcifications and obstructive hydrocephalus, with chorioretinitis leading to visual impairment.<br><br>Congenital toxoplasmosis is diagnosed on maternal serology (positive IgM for Toxoplasma gondii indicates recent infection) and confirmed by fetal sampling or PCR of amniotic fluid.<br><br>Deafness, microcephaly and cataracts (B) characterise congenital rubella; hydrops, anaemia and jaundice (C) suggest haemolytic disease of the newborn; rash, fever and hepatosplenomegaly (D) suggest congenital syphilis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Congenital rubella syndrome commonly presents with:',
  o:['Hydrops fetalis','Cataracts, deafness, heart defects','Intracranial calcifications','Microcephaly only'],a:1,
  e:`Congenital rubella syndrome classically presents with the triad of cataracts, sensorineural deafness and congenital heart defects (most commonly patent ductus arteriosus): the risk of congenital rubella infection reduces with increasing gestation, with the highest risk of severe defects occurring in the first trimester.<br><br>Around 100,000 children every year are born with congenital rubella syndrome globally; the best prevention is maternal vaccination before pregnancy.<br><br>Hydrops fetalis (A) is associated with parvovirus B19; intracranial calcifications (C) are characteristic of toxoplasmosis and CMV; microcephaly alone (D) is associated with congenital CMV and Zika.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Cytomegalovirus infection in pregnancy most commonly causes:',
  o:['Neural tube defects','Polyhydramnios','Macrosomia','Microcephaly'],a:3,
  e:`Cytomegalovirus (CMV) is the most common congenital viral infection worldwide: primary infection is more likely to cause symptomatic congenital CMV (40%), with microcephaly, sensorineural hearing loss and periventricular calcifications being the most recognised manifestations.<br><br>Of those with congenital CMV, it is estimated that 13% will have problems at birth, including microcephaly and hearing loss.<br><br>Neural tube defects (A) relate to folate deficiency; polyhydramnios (B) is associated with fetal swallowing disorders; macrosomia (C) is associated with gestational diabetes.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common congenital viral infection worldwide is:',
  o:['Toxoplasmosis','Rubella','Cytomegalovirus','Herpes simplex'],a:2,
  e:`Cytomegalovirus (CMV) is the most common congenital viral infection worldwide: primary infection during pregnancy is more likely to cause symptomatic congenital CMV (40%), whereas reactivation is less commonly associated with fetal damage.<br><br>Of fetuses with congenital CMV, 13% will have problems at birth including microcephaly, sensorineural hearing loss and periventricular calcifications.<br><br>Toxoplasmosis (A) is a protozoal, not viral, infection; rubella (B) has been substantially reduced by vaccination; herpes simplex (D) is the cause of neonatal herpes, which is less common than congenital CMV.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Syphilis during pregnancy is caused by:',
  o:['Treponema pallidum','Neisseria gonorrhoeae','Chlamydia trachomatis','Streptococcus pyogenes'],a:0,
  e:`Syphilis is caused by Treponema pallidum, a spirochaete: women continue to be routinely screened for syphilis in pregnancy, with a positive screen occurring in approximately 0.15% of screened UK pregnancies, and around 1,400 children born to women requiring treatment.<br><br>Parenteral penicillin has a 98% success rate for preventing congenital syphilis when treatment is given in pregnancy.<br><br>Neisseria gonorrhoeae (B) causes gonorrhoea; Chlamydia trachomatis (C) causes chlamydia; Streptococcus pyogenes (D) is a cause of puerperal sepsis, not syphilis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The screening test commonly used for syphilis in pregnancy is:',
  o:['PCR for Treponema pallidum','ELISA for IgM','Culture of genital swab','VDRL test'],a:3,
  e:`The VDRL (Venereal Disease Research Laboratory) test is a non-treponemal test used as the standard screening tool for syphilis in pregnancy: women continue to be routinely screened for syphilis in pregnancy as part of the antenatal booking screen.<br><br>Positive screening tests are confirmed with specific treponemal antibody tests such as TPHA or TPPA.<br><br>PCR (A) is used for direct detection in specific circumstances; ELISA for IgM (B) and genital culture (C) are not standard syphilis screening methods in antenatal care.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Untreated maternal syphilis may result in:',
  o:['Gestational diabetes','Congenital syphilis','Placenta praevia','Gestational hypertension'],a:1,
  e:`Mother-to-child transmission of syphilis in pregnancy is associated with fetal growth restriction, fetal hydrops and congenital syphilis, which may cause hepatosplenomegaly, skin lesions (snuffles), bone changes and stillbirth: parenteral penicillin has a 98% success rate for preventing congenital syphilis.<br><br>Around 1,400 children born to women requiring treatment had confirmed congenital syphilis in UK data.<br><br>Gestational diabetes (A), placenta praevia (C) and gestational hypertension (D) are not caused by syphilis infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The drug of choice for treating syphilis during pregnancy is:',
  o:['Azithromycin','Doxycycline','Penicillin','Erythromycin'],a:2,
  e:`Parenteral penicillin has a 98% success rate for preventing congenital syphilis and remains the drug of choice for treating syphilis during pregnancy: no proven alternative to penicillin has been established for treating syphilis in pregnancy.<br><br>Women who are penicillin-allergic should be desensitised and treated with penicillin, as alternative antibiotics do not reliably cross the placenta to treat the fetus.<br><br>Azithromycin (A) has been associated with treatment failures; doxycycline (B) is contraindicated in pregnancy due to effects on fetal bone and teeth; erythromycin (D) does not reliably prevent congenital syphilis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Gonorrhoea infection is caused by:',
  o:['Treponema pallidum','Neisseria gonorrhoeae','Chlamydia trachomatis','Gardnerella vaginalis'],a:1,
  e:`Gonorrhoea is caused by Neisseria gonorrhoeae, a gram-negative diplococcus: it is a sexually transmitted infection that in pregnancy is associated with preterm labour, premature rupture of membranes and neonatal conjunctivitis (ophthalmia neonatorum) if transmitted during delivery.<br><br>Neonatal conjunctivitis caused by gonorrhoea (ophthalmia neonatorum) typically presents within 48 hours of birth with purulent eye discharge.<br><br>Treponema pallidum (A) causes syphilis; Chlamydia trachomatis (C) causes chlamydial infection; Gardnerella vaginalis (D) is associated with bacterial vaginosis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'A common complication of untreated gonorrhoea in pregnancy is:',
  o:['Macrosomia','Post-term pregnancy','Preterm labour','Polyhydramnios'],a:2,
  e:`Untreated gonorrhoea in pregnancy is associated with preterm labour, premature rupture of membranes and neonatal conjunctivitis (ophthalmia neonatorum): ascending infection from the cervix causes chorioamnionitis, which stimulates prostaglandin release and precipitates preterm labour.<br><br>Neonatal conjunctivitis from gonorrhoea presents within 48 hours of birth with purulent discharge and requires urgent treatment to prevent corneal scarring.<br><br>Macrosomia (A), post-term pregnancy (B) and polyhydramnios (D) are not recognised complications of gonorrhoea in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'Chlamydia trachomatis infection during pregnancy can cause:',
  o:['Diabetes mellitus','Neonatal conjunctivitis','Neural tube defects','Post-term pregnancy'],a:1,
  e:`Chlamydia trachomatis is a common STI that, if present in the birth canal, can be transmitted to the neonate during vaginal delivery causing neonatal conjunctivitis (inclusion conjunctivitis) and neonatal pneumonia: Chlamydia trachomatis puerperal parametritis may also develop in one-third of women who had a pre-existing infection.<br><br>Chlamydia is among the miscellaneous organisms listed in association with puerperal genital infection.<br><br>Diabetes mellitus (A), neural tube defects (C) and post-term pregnancy (D) are not caused by Chlamydia trachomatis infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 15: The Puerperium)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common manifestation of congenital CMV infection is:',
  o:['Cardiac defects','Limb deformities','Neural tube defects','Sensorineural hearing loss'],a:3,
  e:`Sensorineural hearing loss is the most common and clinically significant long-term manifestation of congenital CMV infection: it may be present at birth or develop progressively in the first years of life, making congenital CMV the leading non-genetic cause of sensorineural hearing loss in children.<br><br>Of those with congenital CMV, 13% will have problems at birth, with sensorineural hearing loss and microcephaly being the most recognised findings.<br><br>Cardiac defects (A) characterise congenital rubella; limb deformities (B) and neural tube defects (C) are not characteristic manifestations of congenital CMV.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Which infection can cause erythema infectiosum (fifth disease)?',
  o:['Rubella virus','Cytomegalovirus','Parvovirus B19','Varicella virus'],a:2,
  e:`Slapped cheek syndrome : also known as erythema infectiosum or fifth disease : is caused by infection with parvovirus B19: a recent infection is characterised by the presence of IgM to parvovirus, whereas a previous infection is characterised by IgG antibodies.<br><br>The main fetal risk is severe anaemia leading to hydrops fetalis, and Doppler of the middle cerebral artery is used to monitor for fetal anaemia after maternal exposure.<br><br>Rubella (A) causes congenital rubella syndrome; cytomegalovirus (B) causes the most common congenital viral infection; varicella (D) causes chickenpox and congenital varicella syndrome.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Which TORCH infection is associated with periventricular calcifications in the fetus?',
  o:['Toxoplasmosis','Cytomegalovirus','Herpes simplex virus','Rubella'],a:1,
  e:`Congenital CMV characteristically causes periventricular calcifications : calcifications clustered around the lateral ventricles : along with microcephaly and sensorineural hearing loss: primary CMV infection is more likely to cause symptomatic congenital disease (40%) than reactivation.<br><br>This periventricular distribution distinguishes CMV from toxoplasmosis, which causes more diffuse scattered intracranial calcifications.<br><br>Toxoplasmosis (A) causes scattered intracranial calcifications; herpes simplex (C) causes encephalitis rather than calcifications; rubella (D) causes cataracts, deafness and cardiac defects.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The main route of transmission of HPV is:',
  o:['Blood transfusion','Respiratory droplets','Faecal-oral route','Sexual contact'],a:3,
  e:`Human papillomavirus is primarily transmitted through sexual contact: it is the most common sexually transmitted infection worldwide, with genital HPV infection being almost universal among sexually active individuals at some point in their lives.<br><br>HPV infection may present as genital warts (caused by low-risk types 6 and 11) or may be asymptomatic, with high-risk types 16 and 18 associated with cervical cancer.<br><br>Blood transfusion (A), respiratory droplets (B) and faecal-oral route (C) are not routes of HPV transmission.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'The vaccine used to prevent HPV infection protects mainly against types:',
  o:['1 and 2','6, 11, 16 and 18','31 and 33','16, 18 and 31'],a:1,
  e:`The HPV vaccine protecting against types 6, 11, 16 and 18 has been introduced in national immunisation programmes: types 16 and 18 are the high-risk oncogenic types responsible for approximately 70% of cervical cancers, while types 6 and 11 cause genital warts.<br><br>The quadrivalent vaccine thus protects against both the most common cause of cervical cancer and the most common cause of genital warts.<br><br>Types 1 and 2 (A) are cutaneous HPV types; types 31 and 33 (C) and 16, 18 and 31 (D) do not represent standard vaccine formulations.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'Which STI is commonly associated with pelvic inflammatory disease?',
  o:['Herpes simplex virus','Hepatitis B virus','Chlamydia trachomatis','Treponema pallidum'],a:2,
  e:`Chlamydia trachomatis is one of the most common causes of pelvic inflammatory disease (PID): ascending infection from the cervix reaches the upper genital tract causing endometritis, salpingitis and oophoritis, with the risk of tubal damage and subsequent infertility.<br><br>Chlamydia trachomatis puerperal parametritis may also develop in one-third of women who had a pre-existing infection at delivery.<br><br>Herpes simplex virus (A) and hepatitis B (B) are not causes of PID; Treponema pallidum (D) causes syphilis and can cause pelvic infection but is less commonly associated with PID than Chlamydia.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'Neonatal conjunctivitis caused by gonorrhoea is called:',
  o:['Trachoma','Dacryocystitis','Uveitis','Ophthalmia neonatorum'],a:3,
  e:`Neonatal conjunctivitis caused by Neisseria gonorrhoeae is specifically termed ophthalmia neonatorum: it presents within 48 hours of birth with profuse purulent eye discharge and requires urgent treatment to prevent corneal ulceration and blindness.<br><br>Untreated gonorrhoea in pregnancy is associated with neonatal conjunctivitis if transmitted during vaginal delivery.<br><br>Trachoma (A) is caused by Chlamydia trachomatis in endemic regions; dacryocystitis (B) is inflammation of the tear sac; uveitis (C) is intraocular inflammation not related to neonatal gonococcal infection.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'Which infection in early pregnancy causes highest risk of congenital anomalies?',
  o:['Rubella','Hepatitis B','Parvovirus B19','Toxoplasmosis'],a:0,
  e:`Rubella infection in the first trimester carries the highest risk of congenital anomalies: the risk of congenital rubella infection reduces with gestation, with the greatest severity of fetal damage : including cataracts, deafness and cardiac defects : occurring during organogenesis in the first trimester.<br><br>More than 100,000 children every year are born with congenital rubella syndrome globally.<br><br>Hepatitis B (B) and parvovirus B19 (C) do not primarily cause structural congenital anomalies; toxoplasmosis (D) causes serious fetal damage but has the highest anomaly risk with first-trimester infection, similar to rubella : however, rubella is the classic answer for highest anomaly risk.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The best prevention for congenital rubella syndrome is:',
  o:['Antiviral therapy during pregnancy','Maternal vaccination before pregnancy','Screening only during pregnancy','Neonatal immunoglobulin'],a:1,
  e:`The aim of rubella screening in pregnancy is to identify susceptible women so that postpartum vaccination may protect future pregnancies: vaccination during pregnancy is contraindicated because of a theoretical risk of teratogenicity, as MMR is a live vaccine.<br><br>The best prevention for congenital rubella syndrome is maternal MMR vaccination before pregnancy, ensuring immunity before conception.<br><br>Antiviral therapy (A) has no role in rubella prevention; screening alone (C) does not prevent infection in the current pregnancy; neonatal immunoglobulin (D) is not used for rubella prevention.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Vertical transmission of HIV can occur during:',
  o:['First trimester only','Second trimester only','Labour, delivery and breastfeeding','Conception only'],a:2,
  e:`Mother-to-child transmission of HIV mainly occurs in the late third trimester, during labour, delivery or breastfeeding: in the UK, where safe infant feeding alternatives are available, all HIV-positive women should be advised not to breastfeed as this increases the risk of mother-to-child transmission.<br><br>Antiretroviral therapy given antenatally, intrapartum and to the neonate for the first 4–6 weeks of life is the cornerstone of prevention.<br><br>First trimester only (A) and second trimester only (B) are incorrect : intrapartum and postnatal transmission are the dominant routes; conception (D) is not a route of HIV transmission.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common symptom of acute hepatitis infection is:',
  o:['Severe itching','Chest pain','Haematuria','Jaundice'],a:3,
  e:`Viral hepatitis is the commonest cause of jaundice in pregnancy worldwide: the clinical features of hepatitis are no different to the non-pregnant patient, with jaundice : resulting from hepatocellular damage and impaired bilirubin conjugation and excretion : being the most common presenting symptom.<br><br>Acute viral hepatitis in the first trimester of pregnancy is associated with a higher rate of spontaneous miscarriage.<br><br>Severe itching (A) is the hallmark of obstetric cholestasis, not viral hepatitis; chest pain (B) and haematuria (C) are not typical features of acute hepatitis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'The incubation period of hepatitis B virus is approximately:',
  o:['1 to 2 weeks','2 to 4 weeks','6 to 24 weeks','2 to 3 days'],a:2,
  e:`The incubation period of hepatitis B virus is long, typically ranging from 6 to 24 weeks (approximately 1.5–6 months): this extended incubation period means that acute infection may not become apparent until well after the exposure event.<br><br>Acute hepatitis B infection occurs in 1–2 per 1,000 pregnancies, and 1.5% of pregnant women are chronic carriers of HBsAg.<br><br>1–2 weeks (A) is the incubation period of influenza; 2–4 weeks (B) is more consistent with hepatitis A; 2–3 days (D) is too short for hepatitis B.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'Which infection is strongly associated with genital warts?',
  o:['Human papillomavirus','Herpes simplex virus','Treponema pallidum','Neisseria gonorrhoeae'],a:0,
  e:`Genital warts (condyloma acuminata) are caused by human papillomavirus, specifically the low-risk types 6 and 11: the HPV vaccine protecting against types 6, 11, 16 and 18 therefore also prevents genital warts in addition to cervical cancer.<br><br>HPV infection may present as genital warts or may be asymptomatic, with high-risk types causing cervical intraepithelial neoplasia and cancer.<br><br>Herpes simplex virus (B) causes painful vesicular ulcers, not warts; Treponema pallidum (C) causes a painless chancre in primary syphilis; Neisseria gonorrhoeae (D) causes purulent urethral and cervical discharge.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'Condyloma acuminata is caused by:',
  o:['Herpes simplex virus','Treponema pallidum','Human papillomavirus','Neisseria gonorrhoeae'],a:2,
  e:`Condyloma acuminata (anogenital warts) is caused by human papillomavirus, predominantly types 6 and 11: HPV infection may present as genital warts and the primary route of transmission is sexual contact.<br><br>The quadrivalent HPV vaccine protects against types 6 and 11 (which cause warts) and types 16 and 18 (which cause cervical cancer).<br><br>Herpes simplex virus (A) causes vesicular ulcers; Treponema pallidum (B) causes the painless chancre of primary syphilis; Neisseria gonorrhoeae (D) causes gonorrhoea with purulent discharge.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'Which TORCH infection is most associated with intracranial calcifications and hydrocephalus?',
  o:['Rubella','Cytomegalovirus','Herpes simplex virus','Toxoplasmosis'],a:3,
  e:`Congenital toxoplasmosis classically causes the triad of chorioretinitis, hydrocephalus and intracranial calcifications: the parasite has a tropism for neural tissue, causing periventricular calcifications and obstructive hydrocephalus.<br><br>The infection results from maternal ingestion of undercooked meat or contact with cat faeces during pregnancy; positive IgM for Toxoplasma gondii indicates recent primary infection.<br><br>Rubella (A) causes cataracts, deafness and cardiac defects; CMV (B) causes periventricular calcifications specifically (not diffuse); herpes simplex (C) causes encephalitis rather than hydrocephalus and calcifications.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Which infection may cause severe anaemia and hydrops fetalis during pregnancy?',
  o:['Parvovirus B19','Hepatitis B','Cytomegalovirus','Rubella'],a:0,
  e:`Parvovirus B19 infection preferentially infects erythroid precursor cells, causing aplastic anaemia in the fetus: this severe fetal anaemia leads to high-output cardiac failure, fluid accumulation and hydrops fetalis, which can be detected by faster flow on middle cerebral artery Doppler.<br><br>If the fetus is confirmed to be anaemic, intrauterine blood transfusion can be considered to prolong the pregnancy until recovery.<br><br>Hepatitis B (B) primarily causes neonatal liver disease; CMV (C) causes microcephaly and hearing loss; rubella (D) causes structural cardiac and eye defects : none of these primarily cause hydrops through severe anaemia.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'Which virus is associated with Kaposi sarcoma in HIV patients?',
  o:['Epstein-Barr virus','Cytomegalovirus','Human herpesvirus 8','Hepatitis C virus'],a:2,
  e:`Kaposi sarcoma in HIV patients is associated with human herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8), also known as Kaposi sarcoma-associated herpesvirus (KSHV): it is an AIDS-defining illness that occurs when immune suppression from HIV allows opportunistic herpesvirus replication and tumour formation.<br><br>HIV infection leads to a progressive reduction in CD4 T cells, eventually allowing opportunistic infections and malignancies to develop.<br><br>Epstein-Barr virus (A) is associated with lymphomas in HIV; CMV (B) causes retinitis and colitis in AIDS; hepatitis C (D) is associated with hepatocellular carcinoma, not Kaposi sarcoma.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'Which infection can cause microcephaly, intracranial calcifications, and sensorineural hearing loss in the fetus?',
  o:['Cytomegalovirus','Hepatitis B','Rubella','Parvovirus B19'],a:0,
  e:`Congenital CMV is the most common congenital viral infection worldwide and is the leading cause of the triad of microcephaly, periventricular intracranial calcifications and sensorineural hearing loss: 13% of congenitally infected infants will have problems at birth, and sensorineural hearing loss may develop progressively even in those who appear normal at birth.<br><br>Primary CMV infection during pregnancy is more likely to cause symptomatic congenital disease (40%) than reactivation.<br><br>Hepatitis B (B) causes neonatal liver disease; rubella (C) causes cataracts, deafness and cardiac defects; parvovirus B19 (D) causes anaemia and hydrops, not microcephaly.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'The causative agent of COVID-19 is:',
  o:['Influenza A virus','Respiratory syncytial virus','Rhinovirus','SARS-CoV-2'],a:3,
  e:`COVID-19 is caused by SARS-CoV-2 (severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2), a single-stranded RNA betacoronavirus: it emerged in late 2019 and caused a global pandemic, with pregnant women identified as a vulnerable group at higher risk of severe disease.<br><br>Severe COVID-19 infection in pregnancy increases the risk of preterm birth, intensive care admission and maternal death in severe cases.<br><br>Influenza A (A), respiratory syncytial virus (B) and rhinovirus (C) are all respiratory viruses but are distinct from the coronavirus causing COVID-19.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'The primary mode of transmission of COVID-19 is:',
  o:['Faecal-oral route','Respiratory droplets and aerosols','Blood-to-blood contact','Mosquito bite'],a:1,
  e:`SARS-CoV-2 is primarily transmitted through respiratory droplets and aerosols produced when an infected person breathes, talks, coughs or sneezes: close contact in poorly ventilated spaces carries the highest transmission risk.<br><br>In pregnancy, severe COVID-19 infection increases the risk of preterm birth, maternal ICU admission and respiratory failure requiring ventilatory support.<br><br>Faecal-oral (A) and blood-to-blood (C) routes are not primary routes for COVID-19; mosquito bite (D) transmits dengue and malaria, not COVID-19.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'Which symptom is most commonly associated with COVID-19 infection?',
  o:['Fever and cough','Haematuria','Severe jaundice','Joint pain only'],a:0,
  e:`Fever and cough are the most common presenting symptoms of COVID-19, along with loss of taste and smell (anosmia/ageusia) and fatigue: the clinical spectrum ranges from asymptomatic infection to severe pneumonia with hypoxia and bilateral lung infiltrates.<br><br>Severe COVID-19 in pregnancy increases the risk of preterm birth and maternal respiratory failure.<br><br>Haematuria (B) suggests urinary tract or renal pathology; severe jaundice (C) suggests hepatic disease; joint pain alone (D) is not a characteristic feature of COVID-19.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common haematological abnormality seen in COVID-19 infection is:',
  o:['Polycythaemia','Thrombocytosis','Lymphopenia','Neutropenia'],a:2,
  e:`Lymphopenia is the most common haematological abnormality in COVID-19 infection, reflecting direct viral depletion of lymphocytes and the associated immune dysregulation: it is seen in the majority of hospitalised patients and correlates with disease severity.<br><br>COVID-19 infection is also associated with hypercoagulability, increasing the risk of venous thromboembolism, which is already elevated in pregnancy.<br><br>Polycythaemia (A) and thrombocytosis (B) are not characteristic of COVID-19; neutropenia (D) is less common than lymphopenia in viral infections.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'The gold standard test for diagnosis of COVID-19 infection is:',
  o:['Chest X-ray','Antibody serology','CT scan of chest','RT-PCR for SARS-CoV-2'],a:3,
  e:`RT-PCR (reverse transcriptase polymerase chain reaction) for SARS-CoV-2 RNA from a nasopharyngeal swab is the gold standard diagnostic test for COVID-19: it directly detects viral genetic material and has high sensitivity and specificity when performed at the appropriate stage of infection.<br><br>Rapid antigen tests are used for point-of-care screening but RT-PCR remains the confirmatory standard.<br><br>Chest X-ray (A) and CT chest (C) show pulmonary involvement but are not diagnostic for COVID-19 specifically; antibody serology (B) indicates past infection or vaccination, not active infection.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'Which complication of COVID-19 is related to hypercoagulability?',
  o:['Hypoglycaemia','Venous thromboembolism','Hypokalaemia','Anaemia'],a:1,
  e:`COVID-19 infection is associated with a hypercoagulable state through endothelial injury, platelet activation and elevated fibrinogen: this significantly increases the risk of venous thromboembolism : deep vein thrombosis and pulmonary embolism : particularly in hospitalised patients.<br><br>In pregnancy, where the coagulation system is already shifted toward hypercoagulability, severe COVID-19 further amplifies this risk.<br><br>Hypoglycaemia (A), hypokalaemia (C) and anaemia (D) are not the primary complications related to the hypercoagulable state in COVID-19.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'In pregnancy, severe COVID-19 infection increases the risk of:',
  o:['Post-term pregnancy','Fetal macrosomia','Preterm birth','Polyhydramnios'],a:2,
  e:`Severe COVID-19 infection in pregnancy is associated with an increased risk of preterm birth, both spontaneous and iatrogenic due to maternal deterioration requiring early delivery: pregnant women with severe COVID-19 also have increased rates of ICU admission, mechanical ventilation and caesarean section.<br><br>The inflammatory response and hypoxia associated with severe maternal infection contribute to preterm labour and placental complications.<br><br>Post-term pregnancy (A), fetal macrosomia (B) and polyhydramnios (D) are not recognised complications of COVID-19 in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'Dengue fever is caused by:',
  o:['Plasmodium falciparum','Flavivirus (dengue virus)','SARS-CoV-2','Parvovirus B19'],a:1,
  e:`Dengue fever is caused by the dengue virus, a flavivirus with four serotypes (DENV-1 to DENV-4): it is transmitted by the Aedes aegypti mosquito and is endemic in tropical and subtropical regions including South Asia, Southeast Asia and Latin America.<br><br>In pregnancy, dengue infection is associated with preterm birth, low birthweight and maternal complications including haemorrhage.<br><br>Plasmodium falciparum (A) causes malaria; SARS-CoV-2 (C) causes COVID-19; parvovirus B19 (D) causes fifth disease and fetal hydrops.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'Dengue virus is transmitted by:',
  o:['Anopheles mosquito','Culex mosquito','Sandfly','Aedes mosquito'],a:3,
  e:`Dengue virus is transmitted by the Aedes aegypti mosquito, which is also the vector for Zika and chikungunya viruses: unlike the Anopheles mosquito that transmits malaria, the Aedes mosquito bites predominantly during the day.<br><br>Dengue infection in pregnancy is associated with preterm birth, low birthweight and maternal thrombocytopenia with haemorrhagic complications.<br><br>Anopheles mosquito (A) transmits malaria; Culex mosquito (B) transmits Japanese encephalitis and West Nile virus; sandfly (C) transmits leishmaniasis.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'The most common clinical feature of dengue fever is:',
  o:['Jaundice','High fever with severe myalgia','Haematuria','Chest pain'],a:1,
  e:`Dengue fever classically presents with high fever, severe headache, retro-orbital pain, severe myalgia and arthralgia : the intense muscle and joint pain has given it the name "breakbone fever": a characteristic skin rash may also develop as the fever subsides.<br><br>In pregnancy, dengue is associated with preterm birth, low birthweight and significant maternal morbidity through thrombocytopenia and plasma leakage.<br><br>Jaundice (A) may occur in severe dengue but is not the most common feature; haematuria (C) and chest pain (D) are not characteristic presenting features of dengue fever.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'Dengue haemorrhagic fever is characterised by:',
  o:['High fever with mild rash only','Respiratory failure only','Haemorrhage with plasma leakage and thrombocytopenia','Encephalitis and seizures'],a:2,
  e:`Dengue haemorrhagic fever is defined by plasma leakage, haemorrhagic manifestations and thrombocytopenia: the vascular permeability and plasma leakage cause haemoconcentration and can progress to dengue shock syndrome with hypotension, tachycardia and circulatory failure.<br><br>Thrombocytopenia is the typical laboratory finding in dengue infection, distinguishing it from other febrile illnesses.<br><br>High fever with mild rash only (A) describes classical dengue fever; respiratory failure (B) and encephalitis (D) are less common complications rather than defining features of dengue haemorrhagic fever.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'Which laboratory finding is typical in dengue infection?',
  o:['Thrombocytopenia','Polycythaemia','Neutrophilia','Hypercalcaemia'],a:0,
  e:`Thrombocytopenia (low platelet count) is the most characteristic laboratory finding in dengue infection, occurring due to both bone marrow suppression and peripheral platelet destruction: in dengue haemorrhagic fever, thrombocytopenia is combined with evidence of plasma leakage and haemoconcentration.<br><br>A platelet count below 100,000/µL is used as part of the case definition for dengue haemorrhagic fever.<br><br>Polycythaemia (B) is the opposite of what occurs; neutrophilia (C) suggests bacterial infection; hypercalcaemia (D) has no association with dengue.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'The confirmatory diagnostic test for dengue infection is:',
  o:['Blood culture','Peripheral smear','Urine culture','NS1 antigen or dengue serology'],a:3,
  e:`NS1 antigen detection is positive in the early febrile phase of dengue infection (days 1–5), while dengue-specific IgM and IgG serology confirms the diagnosis during and after the febrile phase: together these form the confirmatory diagnostic approach for dengue.<br><br>RT-PCR can also be used for direct viral detection in the early phase.<br><br>Blood culture (A) is for bacterial sepsis; peripheral smear (B) diagnoses malaria, not dengue; urine culture (C) diagnoses urinary tract infection.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'A major complication of dengue haemorrhagic fever is:',
  o:['Renal calculi','Dengue shock syndrome','Peptic ulcer disease','Pulmonary tuberculosis'],a:1,
  e:`Dengue shock syndrome is the most serious complication of dengue haemorrhagic fever: massive plasma leakage causes severe hypovolaemia, hypotension and circulatory failure, which can be rapidly fatal if not treated with aggressive fluid resuscitation.<br><br>In pregnancy, dengue infection complicated by shock syndrome carries significant maternal and fetal mortality risk.<br><br>Renal calculi (A), peptic ulcer disease (C) and pulmonary tuberculosis (D) are not complications of dengue haemorrhagic fever.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'Malaria is caused by:',
  o:['Flavivirus','Dengue virus','Plasmodium species','Trypanosoma species'],a:2,
  e:`Malaria is caused by Plasmodium species : a protozoan parasite: although malaria can be caused by four species (P. falciparum, P. vivax, P. ovale and P. malariae), the species carrying the worst prognosis for mother and fetus, and of greatest global importance, is P. falciparum.<br><br>Pregnant women have an increased risk of malarial infection compared to their non-pregnant adult counterparts.<br><br>Flavivirus (A) causes dengue and Zika; dengue virus (B) is a flavivirus causing dengue fever; Trypanosoma species (D) cause sleeping sickness and Chagas disease.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'The vector responsible for transmission of malaria is:',
  o:['Aedes mosquito','Female Anopheles mosquito','Culex mosquito','Sandfly'],a:1,
  e:`Plasmodium falciparum : the most dangerous malarial parasite : is a protozoan parasite transmitted by the female Anopheles mosquito: unlike the Aedes mosquito which bites during the day, the Anopheles mosquito bites predominantly at night.<br><br>In endemic areas, preventive strategies include the use of insecticide-treated bed nets (protecting against nocturnal bites) and intermittent preventive treatment during pregnancy.<br><br>Aedes mosquito (A) transmits dengue and Zika; Culex mosquito (C) transmits Japanese encephalitis; sandfly (D) transmits leishmaniasis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'The most severe form of malaria is caused by:',
  o:['Plasmodium vivax','Plasmodium ovale','Plasmodium malariae','Plasmodium falciparum'],a:3,
  e:`Plasmodium falciparum is the species carrying the worst prognosis for the mother and fetus, and the organism of greatest importance on a worldwide scale: maternal effects include cyclical spiking pyrexia, severe anaemia, hypoglycaemia, pulmonary oedema and haemolysis causing jaundice and renal failure.<br><br>Fetal effects include premature delivery and fetal growth restriction due to placental sequestration of parasites.<br><br>P. vivax (A) and P. ovale (B) can cause relapse through dormant liver hypnozoites; P. malariae (C) is the mildest form; none carries the severity of P. falciparum.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'The classical fever pattern of malaria is:',
  o:['Continuous fever','Cyclical spiking pyrexia','Low-grade persistent fever','Morning fever only'],a:1,
  e:`Maternal effects of malaria include a cyclical spiking pyrexia, which may be associated with miscarriage and preterm labour: the periodicity reflects the synchronised rupture of red blood cells releasing merozoites : every 48 hours in P. falciparum and P. vivax (tertian), and every 72 hours in P. malariae (quartan).<br><br>The classic pattern of fever, chills and rigors follows red cell lysis.<br><br>Continuous fever (A) is more typical of bacterial sepsis; low-grade persistent fever (C) may represent partial treatment or early infection; morning fever only (D) is not the recognised pattern of malaria.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'The gold standard test for malaria diagnosis is:',
  o:['Blood culture','ELISA serology','Peripheral blood smear','Urine dipstick'],a:2,
  e:`Peripheral blood film (smear) examined under microscopy remains the gold standard for malaria diagnosis: it identifies the Plasmodium species, quantifies parasitaemia, and guides management; in endemic areas, malarial parasites may be sequestrated in the placenta even when blood films are negative, requiring a high index of suspicion.<br><br>Rapid diagnostic tests (RDTs) detecting malarial antigens are used at point-of-care where microscopy is not available.<br><br>Blood culture (A) diagnoses bacterial sepsis; ELISA serology (B) indicates past exposure; urine dipstick (D) has no role in malaria diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'Which complication is most commonly associated with severe falciparum malaria?',
  o:['Hypertension','Cerebral malaria','Polycythaemia','Renal stones'],a:1,
  e:`Cerebral malaria is the most feared and common serious complication of P. falciparum infection: it presents with altered consciousness, seizures and coma due to sequestration of parasitised red cells in cerebral microvasculature, causing obstruction of cerebral blood flow.<br><br>Other severe complications of falciparum malaria include pulmonary oedema (with approximately 50% mortality), hypoglycaemia, haemolysis, jaundice and renal failure.<br><br>Hypertension (A) is not caused by malaria; polycythaemia (C) is the opposite of the severe anaemia that occurs; renal stones (D) are not a malaria complication.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'Malaria in pregnancy increases the risk of:',
  o:['Fetal macrosomia','Post-term pregnancy','Gestational diabetes','Preterm delivery and fetal growth restriction'],a:3,
  e:`Fetal effects of malaria in pregnancy include premature delivery and fetal growth restriction: placental sequestration of parasites is associated with abnormal uteroplacental Doppler waveforms and is also implicated in the higher rate of transmission of HIV.<br><br>The incidence of parasitaemia is higher in primiparous women (66%) than in multiparous women (21–29%), suggesting some degree of acquired immunity with successive pregnancies.<br><br>Fetal macrosomia (A), post-term pregnancy (B) and gestational diabetes (C) are not recognised complications of malaria in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'Severe malaria may lead to:',
  o:['Pulmonary oedema and renal failure','Hypertension only','Polycythaemia','Hyperglycaemia'],a:0,
  e:`Severe falciparum malaria causes multiple serious complications: pulmonary oedema due to abnormal capillary permeability results in high mortality (approximately 50%), while haemolysis causes jaundice and renal failure; hypoglycaemia is common and may be severe in pregnancy.<br><br>These complications reflect the systemic endothelial injury and red cell destruction caused by P. falciparum.<br><br>Hypertension alone (B) is not a feature of severe malaria; polycythaemia (C) is the opposite of the severe anaemia that occurs; hyperglycaemia (D) is incorrect : hypoglycaemia is the metabolic complication of severe malaria.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'The rapid diagnostic test for malaria detects:',
  o:['Malarial antibodies','Malarial antigens','Malarial DNA only','Malarial RNA only'],a:1,
  e:`Rapid diagnostic tests (RDTs) for malaria detect malarial antigens : typically histidine-rich protein 2 (HRP-2) specific to P. falciparum, or pan-malarial aldolase : allowing point-of-care diagnosis without microscopy: they provide results within 15–20 minutes and are widely used in resource-limited settings.<br><br>Peripheral blood film microscopy remains the gold standard, but RDTs are valuable in endemic areas where laboratory facilities are limited.<br><br>Malarial antibodies (A) indicate past exposure; malarial DNA (C) and RNA (D) are detected by PCR, which is a research and reference laboratory tool, not a rapid test.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'Which species of Plasmodium can remain dormant in the liver causing relapse?',
  o:['Plasmodium falciparum','Plasmodium malariae','Plasmodium vivax','Plasmodium knowlesi'],a:2,
  e:`Plasmodium vivax (and P. ovale) can form dormant liver stage parasites called hypnozoites, which reactivate weeks to months after the primary infection, causing clinical relapse: this is clinically important as treatment of the acute blood stage infection alone is insufficient : primaquine is required to eradicate liver hypnozoites.<br><br>P. vivax and P. ovale together are the relapsing malarias; P. falciparum and P. malariae do not form hypnozoites.<br><br>P. falciparum (A) is the most dangerous but does not relapse from liver; P. malariae (B) can persist at low levels but does not form hypnozoites; P. knowlesi (D) is a simian malaria without a dormant liver stage.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'Which complication of malaria is characterised by altered consciousness and seizures?',
  o:['Cerebral malaria','Blackwater fever','Splenic rupture','Pulmonary oedema'],a:0,
  e:`Cerebral malaria is defined by altered consciousness and seizures caused by sequestration of P. falciparum-parasitised erythrocytes in cerebral microvasculature: it is a neurological emergency with high mortality and significant risk of neurological sequelae in survivors.<br><br>Prompt symptomatic and supportive treatment with appropriate antimalarial therapy is essential; IV artesunate is the treatment of choice for severe malaria.<br><br>Blackwater fever (B) is massive haemolysis causing haemoglobinuria; splenic rupture (C) is a physical complication; pulmonary oedema (D) causes respiratory failure, not neurological features.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant woman at 34 weeks presents with high fever, severe myalgia, and platelet count of 40,000/µL after returning from a dengue-endemic area. What is the most likely diagnosis?',
  o:['Malaria','Typhoid fever','Chikungunya fever','Dengue haemorrhagic fever'],a:3,
  e:`Dengue haemorrhagic fever is defined by thrombocytopenia (platelet count below 100,000/µL), plasma leakage and haemorrhagic manifestations: a platelet count of 40,000/µL with high fever, severe myalgia and a travel history from a dengue-endemic area constitutes a classic presentation.<br><br>In pregnancy, dengue haemorrhagic fever carries significant maternal and fetal risk including haemorrhage, plasma leakage, shock and preterm birth.<br><br>Malaria (A) causes cyclical fever and anaemia but not typically such severe thrombocytopenia; typhoid (B) causes a stepped fever without the same thrombocytopenic pattern; chikungunya (C) causes severe arthralgia but not haemorrhagic features.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant woman presents with fever every 48 hours associated with chills and rigors. Peripheral smear reveals ring forms of Plasmodium species. Which complication is she most at risk of during pregnancy?',
  o:['Gestational diabetes','Post-term pregnancy','Preterm delivery and fetal growth restriction','Fetal macrosomia'],a:2,
  e:`The cyclical 48-hour fever with chills and rigors, along with ring forms on peripheral smear, confirms malaria: fetal effects of malaria in pregnancy include premature delivery and fetal growth restriction due to placental sequestration of parasites and abnormal uteroplacental Doppler waveforms.<br><br>Maternal effects include severe anaemia, hypoglycaemia and pulmonary oedema; prompt antimalarial therapy is essential.<br><br>Gestational diabetes (A), post-term pregnancy (B) and fetal macrosomia (D) are not recognised complications of malaria in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'A 30-year-old pregnant woman develops severe COVID-19 infection with hypoxia and bilateral lung infiltrates on imaging. Which life-threatening complication is most likely responsible for her respiratory failure?',
  o:['Pulmonary embolism','Acute respiratory distress syndrome','Pneumothorax','Pleural effusion'],a:1,
  e:`Severe COVID-19 pneumonia can progress to acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS), characterised by diffuse alveolar damage, bilateral pulmonary infiltrates and severe hypoxia: this is the most common cause of life-threatening respiratory failure in severe COVID-19.<br><br>Severe COVID-19 infection in pregnancy increases the risk of ICU admission, mechanical ventilation and preterm birth.<br><br>Pulmonary embolism (A) causes acute respiratory compromise but not bilateral infiltrates; pneumothorax (C) causes unilateral collapse; pleural effusion (D) is a different radiological pattern from the bilateral ground-glass opacities of COVID-19 ARDS.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'A traveler returns from a malaria-endemic region with high fever, confusion, and seizures. Blood smear shows Plasmodium falciparum. Which severe complication explains his neurological symptoms?',
  o:['Pulmonary oedema','Hypoglycaemia','Cerebral malaria','Splenic rupture'],a:2,
  e:`Cerebral malaria : the most serious neurological complication of P. falciparum : presents with altered consciousness, confusion and seizures due to sequestration of parasitised erythrocytes in cerebral microvasculature, causing cerebral hypoxia and inflammation.<br><br>P. falciparum is the species carrying the worst prognosis for the mother and fetus, and is responsible for the vast majority of malaria deaths globally.<br><br>Pulmonary oedema (A) causes respiratory failure; hypoglycaemia (B) can contribute to confusion but is not the primary explanation for seizures in this context; splenic rupture (D) causes acute abdominal pain, not neurological features.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant patient with confirmed dengue infection develops hypotension, tachycardia, and signs of plasma leakage. What is the most likely diagnosis?',
  o:['Classical dengue fever','Malaria complication','Puerperal sepsis','Dengue shock syndrome'],a:3,
  e:`Dengue shock syndrome occurs when plasma leakage from dengue haemorrhagic fever is severe enough to cause hypovolaemia and circulatory failure: hypotension, tachycardia and signs of plasma leakage (haemoconcentration, pleural effusion, ascites) define this life-threatening complication.<br><br>Aggressive fluid resuscitation is the cornerstone of management; in pregnancy this carries additional fetal risk.<br><br>Classical dengue fever (A) does not cause haemodynamic compromise; malaria complication (B) and puerperal sepsis (C) are different diagnoses not supported by the clinical context of confirmed dengue.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'A 28-year-old primigravida at 12 weeks develops fever and lymphadenopathy. Serology shows positive IgM for Toxoplasma gondii. Which fetal complication is most strongly associated with congenital infection?',
  o:['Cardiac defects','Chorioretinitis and intracranial calcifications','Limb deformities','Neural tube defects'],a:1,
  e:`Positive IgM for Toxoplasma gondii indicates recent primary infection: the classic complications of congenital toxoplasmosis are chorioretinitis, hydrocephalus and intracranial calcifications, reflecting the parasite's tropism for neural and ocular tissue.<br><br>The risk of fetal transmission is lower in the first trimester, but the severity of damage is greatest with early infection : making first-trimester infection the most concerning for severe neurological and ocular sequelae.<br><br>Cardiac defects (A) and limb deformities (C) are not characteristic of toxoplasmosis; neural tube defects (D) relate to folate deficiency, not toxoplasmosis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant woman at 20 weeks presents with mild fever and malaise. Ultrasound later reveals fetal microcephaly and periventricular calcifications. Which infection is most likely responsible?',
  o:['Toxoplasmosis','Rubella','Cytomegalovirus','Herpes simplex virus'],a:2,
  e:`Congenital CMV is the most common congenital viral infection and classically causes periventricular calcifications with microcephaly and sensorineural hearing loss: primary CMV infection during pregnancy is often mild and flu-like in the mother, while causing significant fetal neurological damage.<br><br>Of infants with congenital CMV, 13% will have problems at birth, and hearing loss may develop progressively even in those appearing normal initially.<br><br>Toxoplasmosis (A) causes diffuse scattered intracranial calcifications rather than periventricular; rubella (B) causes cataracts, deafness and cardiac defects; herpes simplex (D) causes encephalitis but not this pattern of periventricular calcification.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant healthcare worker is exposed to a child with erythema infectiosum. Two weeks later ultrasound shows fetal ascites and cardiomegaly. What is the underlying fetal mechanism?',
  o:['Cardiac malformation','Placental insufficiency','Renal failure','Severe fetal anaemia causing high-output cardiac failure'],a:3,
  e:`Erythema infectiosum (fifth disease) is caused by parvovirus B19: the virus infects fetal erythroid precursor cells causing aplastic anaemia, which leads to severe fetal anaemia, high-output cardiac failure, cardiomegaly, fluid accumulation and hydrops fetalis.<br><br>A middle cerebral artery Doppler confirms fetal anaemia by showing increased flow velocity; intrauterine blood transfusion can be considered if anaemia is severe.<br><br>Cardiac malformation (A) and placental insufficiency (B) cause fetal compromise but are not the mechanism of parvovirus-associated hydrops; renal failure (C) is not involved in this process.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A woman at 34 weeks gestation presents with intense pruritus, elevated liver enzymes, and positive hepatitis E serology. Which complication is most feared in pregnancy?',
  o:['Neonatal jaundice only','Maternal hypertension','Fulminant hepatic failure','Renal calculi'],a:2,
  e:`Hepatitis E is more likely to lead to fulminant hepatic failure in pregnancy than in non-pregnant individuals: in underdeveloped countries, 20% of women infected in the third trimester die of fulminant hepatitis, making it the hepatitis virus with the highest maternal mortality in pregnancy.<br><br>It is more common in primigravidae and the third trimester, with significant associations with preterm delivery, fetal growth restriction and stillbirth.<br><br>Neonatal jaundice only (A) underestimates the severity; maternal hypertension (B) is not caused by hepatitis E; renal calculi (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant woman with untreated syphilis delivers a stillborn fetus with hepatosplenomegaly and skin lesions. Which diagnostic test during pregnancy would most likely have identified the infection early?',
  o:['VDRL test','Blood culture','Urine culture','Cervical swab PCR'],a:0,
  e:`Women continue to be routinely screened for syphilis in pregnancy using the VDRL test: a positive screen occurs in approximately 0.15% of screened UK pregnancies, and parenteral penicillin has a 98% success rate for preventing congenital syphilis when treatment is given in pregnancy.<br><br>Mother-to-child transmission of syphilis is associated with fetal growth restriction, fetal hydrops and congenital syphilis causing hepatosplenomegaly, skin lesions and stillbirth.<br><br>Blood culture (B) and urine culture (C) are not used for syphilis screening; cervical swab PCR (D) is used for Chlamydia and gonorrhoea, not syphilis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A neonate born to an untreated HIV-positive mother develops infection. Which factor most strongly increases vertical transmission risk?',
  o:['Early gestational age','Low maternal weight','High maternal viral load','Maternal anaemia'],a:2,
  e:`The principal risks of mother-to-child vertical transmission are related to maternal plasma viral load, obstetric factors and infant feeding: a high maternal viral load at delivery is the strongest predictor of vertical transmission, which is why antiretroviral therapy : reducing viral load to undetectable levels : is the cornerstone of prevention.<br><br>Interventions including antiretroviral therapy can reduce transmission from 25–30% to less than 2%.<br><br>Early gestational age (A), low maternal weight (B) and maternal anaemia (D) are not the primary drivers of vertical HIV transmission risk.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant woman with active genital herpes lesions presents in labour. Which management strategy best prevents neonatal infection?',
  o:['Caesarean section','Vaginal delivery with aciclovir','Forceps delivery','Observation only'],a:0,
  e:`Caesarean section is recommended in active genital herpes infection to prevent neonatal herpes acquired during passage through the birth canal: neonatal herpes is most commonly acquired during vaginal delivery in the presence of active maternal genital lesions, and carries high morbidity and mortality.<br><br>The risk is highest with primary maternal HSV infection at delivery, when protective maternal antibodies have not yet developed and transferred to the fetus.<br><br>Vaginal delivery with aciclovir (B) does not adequately protect the neonate in active primary infection; forceps delivery (C) increases trauma and inoculation risk; observation only (D) is never appropriate in active genital herpes at term.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A fetus is found to have hydrops fetalis with severe anaemia on Doppler study after maternal viral illness. Which investigation confirms the suspected infection?',
  o:['Hepatitis B serology','CMV PCR','Rubella IgG','Maternal parvovirus B19 IgM'],a:3,
  e:`A recent parvovirus B19 infection is characterised by the presence of IgM to parvovirus in maternal serum: the diagnosis of acute parvovirus infection causing fetal hydrops can be confirmed with a maternal blood test confirming IgM and/or new IgG antibodies, and amniotic fluid can additionally be tested by PCR.<br><br>The main effect of parvovirus infection is severe fetal anaemia detected by increased middle cerebral artery Doppler flow velocity.<br><br>Hepatitis B serology (A), CMV PCR (B) and rubella IgG (C) are investigations for different infections and would not confirm parvovirus-associated fetal hydrops.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A newborn presents with cataracts, sensorineural deafness, and patent ductus arteriosus. Maternal infection during pregnancy most likely involved which pathogen?',
  o:['Cytomegalovirus','Parvovirus B19','Rubella virus','Toxoplasma gondii'],a:2,
  e:`The classic triad of cataracts, sensorineural deafness and congenital heart defects (particularly patent ductus arteriosus) is pathognomonic of congenital rubella syndrome: this results from first-trimester maternal rubella infection during organogenesis, when the fetus is most vulnerable.<br><br>Features of congenital rubella syndrome can include sensorineural deafness, congenital cataracts, blindness, encephalitis and endocrine problems.<br><br>CMV (A) causes microcephaly and periventricular calcifications; parvovirus B19 (B) causes anaemia and hydrops; toxoplasmosis (D) causes chorioretinitis, hydrocephalus and intracranial calcifications.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant woman presents with high fever, thrombocytopenia, and plasma leakage after dengue infection. Which complication explains hypotension and shock?',
  o:['Classical dengue fever','Malaria superinfection','Puerperal sepsis','Dengue shock syndrome'],a:3,
  e:`Dengue shock syndrome occurs when massive plasma leakage in dengue haemorrhagic fever causes severe hypovolaemia: the vascular permeability leads to haemoconcentration, pleural effusion, ascites and ultimately circulatory failure with hypotension and tachycardia.<br><br>Aggressive fluid resuscitation is the cornerstone of management; in pregnancy, dengue shock syndrome carries significant maternal and fetal mortality.<br><br>Classical dengue fever (A) does not cause haemodynamic compromise; malaria superinfection (B) is a different diagnosis; puerperal sepsis (C) is not consistent with confirmed dengue as the primary diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'A 32-year-old pregnant woman presents with periodic fever every 48 hours and anaemia. Peripheral smear shows trophozoites in erythrocytes. Which complication is most concerning for the fetus?',
  o:['Fetal macrosomia','Gestational diabetes','Fetal growth restriction and preterm delivery','Polyhydramnios'],a:2,
  e:`The 48-hour cyclical fever with trophozoites on peripheral smear confirms malaria: fetal effects include premature delivery and fetal growth restriction due to placental sequestration of parasites, which causes abnormal uteroplacental Doppler waveforms and reduced nutrient transfer.<br><br>The incidence of parasitaemia is higher in primiparous women (66%) than in multiparous women, suggesting acquired semi-immunity in endemic areas.<br><br>Fetal macrosomia (A), gestational diabetes (B) and polyhydramnios (D) are not recognised fetal complications of malaria in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant woman develops fever and jaundice with positive HBsAg and HBeAg. Which neonatal complication is most likely without prophylaxis?',
  o:['Neonatal anaemia','Chronic hepatitis B infection','Neonatal jaundice only','Congenital malformation'],a:1,
  e:`Without preventive measures, 90% of babies born to mothers who are HBsAg and HBeAg positive (indicating high infectivity) will contract hepatitis B infection: the neonate should receive hepatitis B vaccine plus one dose of hepatitis B immune globulin (HBIG) within the first 12 hours of life, conferring over 95% protection against chronic infection.<br><br>HBeAg positivity specifically indicates active viral replication and high infectivity, substantially increasing vertical transmission risk.<br><br>Neonatal anaemia (A) and congenital malformation (D) are not typical outcomes of neonatal hepatitis B; neonatal jaundice alone (C) underestimates the risk of chronic infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 2: Antenatal Care)</em>`},

    {q:'A patient at 30 weeks gestation develops severe COVID-19 pneumonia with hypoxia. Which obstetric complication is most associated with severe maternal infection?',
  o:['Post-term pregnancy','Fetal macrosomia','Polyhydramnios','Preterm birth'],a:3,
  e:`Severe COVID-19 infection in pregnancy increases the risk of preterm birth : both spontaneous from the systemic inflammatory response and iatrogenic when early delivery is required for maternal deterioration: pregnant women with severe COVID-19 also have increased rates of ICU admission, mechanical ventilation and caesarean section.<br><br>Hypoxia from severe maternal infection directly compromises fetal oxygenation, contributing to preterm labour and placental complications.<br><br>Post-term pregnancy (A), fetal macrosomia (B) and polyhydramnios (C) are not recognised complications of COVID-19 in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'A fetus shows intracranial calcifications and chorioretinitis on ultrasound. Maternal ingestion of undercooked meat earlier in pregnancy is reported. Which infection is responsible?',
  o:['Toxoplasmosis','Cytomegalovirus','Rubella','Herpes simplex virus'],a:0,
  e:`Toxoplasma gondii : a protozoan parasite transmitted through ingestion of undercooked meat containing tissue cysts or contact with cat faeces : causes congenital toxoplasmosis characterised by chorioretinitis, hydrocephalus and intracranial calcifications.<br><br>Positive IgM for Toxoplasma gondii confirms recent primary infection; the diagnosis can be confirmed by fetal sampling or PCR of amniotic fluid.<br><br>CMV (A) causes periventricular calcifications specifically; rubella (B) causes cataracts, deafness and cardiac defects; herpes simplex (D) causes encephalitis, not this pattern of calcification.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant woman with untreated gonorrhoea delivers a newborn who develops purulent conjunctivitis within 48 hours. What is the most likely diagnosis?',
  o:['Chlamydial conjunctivitis','Ophthalmia neonatorum','Viral keratitis','Allergic conjunctivitis'],a:1,
  e:`Ophthalmia neonatorum is neonatal conjunctivitis caused by Neisseria gonorrhoeae, typically presenting within 48 hours of birth with profuse purulent eye discharge: untreated, it rapidly progresses to corneal ulceration and blindness, requiring urgent topical and systemic antibiotic treatment.<br><br>Chlamydial conjunctivitis (inclusion conjunctivitis) presents later, typically at 5–14 days of life.<br><br>Chlamydial conjunctivitis (A) has a later onset; viral keratitis (C) and allergic conjunctivitis (D) do not present with purulent discharge in the neonatal period from a maternal STI source.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant woman develops genital warts during antenatal care. Which virus is responsible for this condition?',
  o:['Herpes simplex virus','Cytomegalovirus','Treponema pallidum','Human papillomavirus'],a:3,
  e:`Genital warts (condyloma acuminata) are caused by human papillomavirus, specifically the low-risk types 6 and 11: HPV infection may present as genital warts and the primary route of transmission is sexual contact.<br><br>The quadrivalent HPV vaccine protects against types 6 and 11 (causing warts) and types 16 and 18 (causing cervical cancer).<br><br>Herpes simplex virus (A) causes painful vesicular ulcers; cytomegalovirus (B) causes congenital infection; Treponema pallidum (C) causes the painless chancre of primary syphilis : none cause genital warts.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},

    {q:'A neonate develops hepatosplenomegaly and thrombocytopenia with "blueberry muffin" rash. Which congenital infection is most likely responsible?',
  o:['Toxoplasmosis','Parvovirus B19','Congenital rubella syndrome','Herpes simplex virus'],a:2,
  e:`The "blueberry muffin" rash : caused by dermal erythropoiesis : combined with hepatosplenomegaly, thrombocytopenia and other features such as cataracts and cardiac defects is classic for congenital rubella syndrome: it results from first-trimester maternal rubella infection during organogenesis.<br><br>Features of congenital rubella syndrome include sensorineural deafness, congenital cataracts, blindness, cardiac defects and thrombocytopenia with the characteristic skin findings.<br><br>Toxoplasmosis (A) causes chorioretinitis and intracranial calcifications; parvovirus B19 (B) causes anaemia and hydrops; herpes simplex (D) causes encephalitis and disseminated disease without this rash pattern.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant woman with untreated HIV infection delivers vaginally without ART. Which neonatal complication is most likely?',
  o:['Congenital malformation','Neonatal HIV infection','Neonatal anaemia','Neonatal hypoglycaemia'],a:1,
  e:`Without antiretroviral therapy, the risk of mother-to-child transmission of HIV is 25–30%: vertical transmission mainly occurs during labour and delivery or through breastfeeding, and vaginal delivery without ART in a woman with a high viral load significantly increases this risk.<br><br>All infants born to HIV-positive women should receive antiretroviral therapy from birth for 4–6 weeks, regardless of maternal treatment status.<br><br>Congenital malformation (A) is not caused by HIV; neonatal anaemia (C) and hypoglycaemia (D) are not primary complications of maternal HIV infection without treatment.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A fetus shows sensorineural hearing loss and microcephaly on postnatal evaluation. Which congenital infection is the most common cause?',
  o:['Toxoplasmosis','Rubella','Cytomegalovirus','Herpes simplex virus'],a:2,
  e:`Congenital CMV is the most common congenital viral infection worldwide and is the leading non-genetic cause of sensorineural hearing loss in children: 13% of congenitally infected infants have problems at birth including microcephaly and hearing loss, and sensorineural hearing loss may develop progressively even in initially asymptomatic infants.<br><br>Primary CMV infection during pregnancy is more likely to cause symptomatic congenital disease (40%) than reactivation.<br><br>Toxoplasmosis (A) causes chorioretinitis and hydrocephalus; rubella (B) causes cataracts, deafness and cardiac defects but is less common than CMV; herpes simplex (D) causes encephalitis rather than sensorineural hearing loss and microcephaly.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant traveler from a malaria-endemic region presents with severe anaemia and fever. Peripheral smear confirms Plasmodium falciparum. Which maternal complication is most likely?',
  o:['Pulmonary oedema and haemolysis','Gestational diabetes','Chronic hypertension','Placenta praevia'],a:0,
  e:`Severe falciparum malaria causes pulmonary oedema due to abnormal capillary permeability : with approximately 50% mortality : and haemolysis leading to jaundice and renal failure: severe anaemia may develop rapidly and hypoglycaemia is common and may be severe in pregnancy.<br><br>P. falciparum carries the worst prognosis for the mother and fetus; prompt antimalarial therapy is essential.<br><br>Gestational diabetes (B), chronic hypertension (C) and placenta praevia (D) are not caused by falciparum malaria.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant woman develops jaundice and elevated liver enzymes after contaminated water exposure. Which virus is most likely responsible?',
  o:['Hepatitis B','Hepatitis C','Cytomegalovirus','Hepatitis E'],a:3,
  e:`Hepatitis E is transmitted via the faecal-oral route through contaminated water, making it the most likely cause of jaundice following contaminated water exposure: it is more likely to lead to fulminant hepatic failure in pregnancy, with a mortality of up to 20% in the third trimester in developing countries.<br><br>It is more common in primagravidae and in the third trimester, with significant associations with preterm delivery and stillbirth.<br><br>Hepatitis B (A) and C (B) are transmitted through blood and body fluids, not contaminated water; CMV (C) is spread through close contact and body fluids, not waterborne transmission.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 10: Medical Complications of Pregnancy)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant patient develops vesicular genital lesions and pain. PCR confirms HSV infection. Which neonatal complication is most feared if transmitted?',
  o:['Neonatal jaundice','Neonatal herpes encephalitis','Neonatal anaemia','Neonatal hypoglycaemia'],a:1,
  e:`Neonatal herpes acquired during vaginal delivery in the presence of active maternal HSV lesions can cause disseminated infection and herpes encephalitis, which carries high mortality and significant neurological morbidity in survivors: antiviral agents such as aciclovir have dramatically improved outcomes when complications occur.<br><br>Caesarean section is recommended in active genital herpes to prevent neonatal transmission during delivery.<br><br>Neonatal jaundice (A), anaemia (C) and hypoglycaemia (D) are not the primary feared complications of neonatal herpes infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A fetus shows ascites, hepatomegaly, and hydrops after maternal viral illness. Which diagnostic test best detects fetal anaemia in this scenario?',
  o:['Amniocentesis for karyotype','Fetal blood sampling','Maternal serology only','Middle cerebral artery Doppler'],a:3,
  e:`Middle cerebral artery (MCA) Doppler is the non-invasive investigation of choice to detect fetal anaemia: faster MCA Doppler flow is indicative of fetal anaemia, as anaemic fetuses increase cardiac output to maintain oxygen delivery, resulting in hyperdynamic circulation detectable on Doppler.<br><br>This has improved the diagnosis and management of fetuses infected with parvovirus B19, as the main effect of this infection is severe fetal anaemia leading to hydrops.<br><br>Amniocentesis for karyotype (A) assesses chromosomes, not anaemia; fetal blood sampling (B) can directly measure haemoglobin but is invasive and follows MCA Doppler assessment; maternal serology only (C) confirms the infection but does not assess fetal anaemia.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant woman with TORCH infection has fetal intracranial calcifications predominantly in periventricular regions. Which infection is most likely?',
  o:['Toxoplasmosis','Rubella','Cytomegalovirus','Herpes simplex virus'],a:2,
  e:`Periventricular calcifications : clustered around the lateral ventricles : are the hallmark of congenital CMV infection: this distribution distinguishes CMV from toxoplasmosis, which causes more diffuse, scattered intracranial calcifications throughout the brain parenchyma.<br><br>Congenital CMV is the most common congenital viral infection and causes the triad of periventricular calcifications, microcephaly and sensorineural hearing loss.<br><br>Toxoplasmosis (A) causes diffuse scattered calcifications; rubella (B) causes structural eye and cardiac defects; herpes simplex (D) causes encephalitis without this calcification pattern.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A neonate develops hepatosplenomegaly and snuffles shortly after birth. Maternal history reveals untreated infection during pregnancy. Which disease is most likely?',
  o:['Congenital CMV','Congenital rubella','Congenital toxoplasmosis','Congenital syphilis'],a:3,
  e:`Hepatosplenomegaly and snuffles (profuse nasal discharge due to rhinitis) in a neonate with a maternal history of untreated infection are classic features of congenital syphilis: mother-to-child transmission of syphilis is associated with hepatosplenomegaly, skin lesions, bone changes and snuffles, all resulting from spirochaetal dissemination.<br><br>Parenteral penicillin has a 98% success rate for preventing congenital syphilis when treatment is given in pregnancy.<br><br>Congenital CMV (A) causes microcephaly and hearing loss; congenital rubella (B) causes cataracts and cardiac defects; congenital toxoplasmosis (C) causes chorioretinitis and hydrocephalus : none classically present with snuffles.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant woman presents with high fever, thrombocytopenia, and plasma leakage after dengue infection. Which complication explains hypotension and shock?',
  o:['Classical dengue only','Dengue shock syndrome','Malaria complication','Septic shock'],a:1,
  e:`Dengue shock syndrome occurs when plasma leakage from dengue haemorrhagic fever is severe enough to cause hypovolaemia and circulatory failure: the massive vascular permeability leads to haemoconcentration, pleural effusions, ascites, hypotension and tachycardia.<br><br>Aggressive fluid resuscitation is the cornerstone of management; thrombocytopenia combined with plasma leakage defines dengue haemorrhagic fever progressing to shock.<br><br>Classical dengue only (A) does not cause haemodynamic compromise; malaria complication (C) and septic shock (D) are different diagnoses not consistent with confirmed dengue.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},

    {q:'A fetus develops hydrops due to maternal parvovirus infection. Which pathophysiological process explains this condition?',
  o:['Placental thrombosis','Cardiac malformation','Renal failure','Severe fetal aplastic anaemia'],a:3,
  e:`Parvovirus B19 infects fetal erythroid precursor cells causing aplastic anaemia: the severe fetal anaemia leads to high-output cardiac failure with cardiomegaly, fluid accumulation in body cavities and hydrops fetalis : this is the primary pathophysiological mechanism.<br><br>Middle cerebral artery Doppler detects the resulting fetal anaemia; intrauterine blood transfusion can reverse the hydrops if performed before irreversible cardiac damage.<br><br>Placental thrombosis (A) and renal failure (C) are not the mechanism; cardiac malformation (B) is not caused by parvovirus : the cardiomegaly is secondary to high-output failure from anaemia.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A pregnant patient tests positive for HBsAg. Which neonatal prophylaxis strategy prevents vertical transmission?',
  o:['Breastfeeding avoidance only','Maternal antiviral therapy alone','Hepatitis B vaccine plus HBIG within 12 hours','Elective caesarean section only'],a:2,
  e:`The infant should receive hepatitis B vaccine and one dose of hepatitis B immune globulin (HBIG) within the first 12 hours of life: this confers over 95% protection against chronic hepatitis B infection, with additional vaccine doses at 1 and 6 months.<br><br>Without these preventive measures, 90% of babies born to highly infectious HBsAg-positive mothers will contract hepatitis B.<br><br>Breastfeeding avoidance alone (A) and elective caesarean section (D) are not recommended standalone strategies for hepatitis B; maternal antiviral therapy alone (B) reduces viral load but is insufficient without neonatal prophylaxis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 2: Antenatal Care)</em>`},

    {q:'A fetus is diagnosed with hydrocephalus and chorioretinitis. Maternal infection occurred after exposure to cat feces. Which infection is most likely responsible?',
  o:['Cytomegalovirus','Rubella','Herpes simplex virus','Toxoplasmosis'],a:3,
  e:`Toxoplasma gondii is transmitted through contact with cat faeces containing oocysts or through ingestion of undercooked meat with tissue cysts: congenital toxoplasmosis classically causes the triad of chorioretinitis, hydrocephalus and intracranial calcifications due to the parasite's tropism for neural and ocular tissue.<br><br>Positive IgM for Toxoplasma gondii confirms recent primary infection; amniotic fluid can be tested for Toxoplasma by PCR.<br><br>CMV (A) causes periventricular calcifications without the cat-faeces exposure history; rubella (B) causes cataracts and cardiac defects; herpes simplex (C) causes encephalitis not hydrocephalus from cat exposure.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`},

    {q:'A neonate develops severe pneumonia and sepsis shortly after birth from maternal genital infection. Which pathogen is most commonly responsible for early neonatal infection?',
  o:['Streptococcus agalactiae (Group B)','Staphylococcus aureus','Escherichia coli','Listeria monocytogenes'],a:0,
  e:`Group B streptococcus (Streptococcus agalactiae) is recognised as the most frequent cause of severe early-onset infection : presenting within 7 days of birth : in newborn infants: it causes neonatal sepsis, pneumonia and meningitis, with transmission occurring from the maternal vagina during delivery.<br><br>The mortality from early-onset GBS disease is 6% in term infants and 18% in preterm infants; intrapartum antibiotic prophylaxis with penicillin is estimated to be 60–80% effective in reducing early-onset neonatal GBS infection.<br><br>Staphylococcus aureus (B) and E. coli (C) can cause neonatal sepsis but are less common; Listeria monocytogenes (D) causes transplacental infection and is not the most common cause of early neonatal sepsis from genital tract infection.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter 11: Perinatal Infections)</em>`}
  ];
})();
